9.3.1.116 Redirection for Voice EPS Fallback - Section Description: This IE is used to indicate that the AMF and the UE support the redirection for voice for EPS Fallback. 8.3.1 Initial Context Setup 8.3.1.2 Successful Operation If the Redirection for Voice EPS Fallback IE is included in the INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store it and use it in a subsequent decision of EPS fallback for voice as specified in TS 23.502 [10].

9.3.1.65 Location Reporting Request Type - Section Description: This IE indicates the type of location request to be handled by the NG-RAN node. 8.3.1 Initial Context Setup 8.3.1.2 Successful Operation If the Location Reporting Request Type IE is included in the INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node should perform the requested location reporting functionality for the UE as described in subclause 8.12.
ENUMERATED (direct, change of serving cell, UE presence in the area of interest, stop change of serving cell, stop UE presence in the area of interest, cancel location reporting for the UE, …)
9.3.1.66 Area of Interest - Section Description: This IE indicates the area of interest.
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
9.3.1.5 Global RAN Node ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NG-RAN node (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.6 Global gNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a gNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.6 gNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE contained in the NR CGI IE of each cell served by the gNB.
9.3.1.8 Global ng-eNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an ng-eNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.8 Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 20 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Short Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 18 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Long Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 21 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.57 Global N3IWF ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an N3IWF.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.76 Location Reporting Reference ID - Section Description: This IE contains the Location Reporting Reference ID.
│  ├─Location Reporting Reference ID to be Cancelled

9.3.1.65 - Location Reporting Reference ID to be Cancelled IE - ifEventTypeisStopUEPresinAoI: This IE shall be present if the Event Type IE is set to "stop UE presence in the area of interest". 9.3.1.76 Location Reporting Reference ID - Section Description: This IE contains the Location Reporting Reference ID.

9.3.1.119 CN Assisted RAN Parameters Tuning - Section Description: This IE provides information for assisting in parameters tuning of the NG-RAN node. 8.3.1 Initial Context Setup 8.3.1.2 Successful Operation If the CN Assisted RAN Parameters Tuning IE is included in the INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node may use it as described in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.119 Expected UE Behaviour IE Semantics: This IE may be present in case the Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE IE is not included and is ignored otherwise. 9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.

9.3.1.128 SRVCC Operation Possible - Section Description: This element indicates that both UE and AMF are SRVCC-capable. NG-RAN behaviour on receipt of this IE is specified in TS 23.216 [31]. 9.3.1.128 SRVCC operation possible IE Semantics: The value "Possible" indicates that UE and AMF are SRVCC capable.

section_list.name: INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP RESPONSE
aoa:
This message is sent by the NG-RAN node to confirm the setup of a UE context.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.3.1 Initial Context Setup 8.3.1.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP RESPONSE message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transfer transparently the PDU Session Resource Setup Response Transfer IE or PDU Session Resource Setup Unsuccessful Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session. In case the splitting PDU session is not used by the NG-RAN node, the SMF should remove the Additional Transport Layer Information, if any.

9.2.2.2 PDU Session Resource Setup Response Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the PDU Session Resource Setup Response Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.2. 8.3.1 Initial Context Setup 8.3.1.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP RESPONSE message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transfer transparently the PDU Session Resource Setup Response Transfer IE or PDU Session Resource Setup Unsuccessful Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session. In case the splitting PDU session is not used by the NG-RAN node, the SMF should remove the Additional Transport Layer Information, if any.
├─PDU Session Resource Failed to Setup List
│  └─PDU Session Resource Failed to Setup Item

9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.3.1 Initial Context Setup 8.3.1.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP RESPONSE message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transfer transparently the PDU Session Resource Setup Response Transfer IE or PDU Session Resource Setup Unsuccessful Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session. In case the splitting PDU session is not used by the NG-RAN node, the SMF should remove the Additional Transport Layer Information, if any.

9.2.2.2 PDU Session Resource Setup Unsuccessful Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the PDU Session Resource Setup Unsuccessful Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.16. 8.3.1 Initial Context Setup 8.3.1.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP RESPONSE message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transfer transparently the PDU Session Resource Setup Response Transfer IE or PDU Session Resource Setup Unsuccessful Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session. In case the splitting PDU session is not used by the NG-RAN node, the SMF should remove the Additional Transport Layer Information, if any.

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.16 Age of Location IE Semantics: Indicates the UTC time when the location information was generated. 9.3.1.75 Time Stamp - Section Description: This IE contains UTC time information. 9.3.1.75 Time Stamp IE Semantics: Encoded in the same format as the first four octets of the 64-bit timestamp format as defined in section 6 of IETF RFC 5905 [25].
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.16 IP Address IE Semantics: UE's local IP address used to reach the N3IWF 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].
9.3.1.16 Port Number IE Semantics: UDP or TCP source port number if NAT is detected.
├─Information on Recommended Cells and RAN Nodes for Paging

9.3.1.100 Information on Recommended Cells and RAN Nodes for Paging - Section Description: This IE provides information on recommended cells and NG-RAN nodes for paging. 8.3.3 UE Context Release (AMF initiated) 8.3.3.2 Successful Operation If the Information on Recommended Cells and RAN Nodes for Paging IE is included in the UE CONTEXT RELEASE COMPLETE message, the AMF shall, if supported, store it and may use it for subsequent paging.
9.3.1.71 Recommended Cells for Paging - Section Description: This IE contains the recommended cells for paging. This IE is transparent to the 5GC.

9.3.1.71 Recommended Cell Item IE Semantics: Includes visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.71 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: This is included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.
9.3.1.101 Recommended RAN Nodes for Paging - Section Description: This IE contains recommended NG-RAN nodes for paging.

9.3.1.101 Recommended RAN Node Item IE Semantics: Includes visited and non-visited NG-RAN nodes, where visited NG-RAN nodes are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent NG-RAN node being the first in the list. Non-visited NG-RAN nodes are included after the visited NG-RAN node they are associated with.
9.3.1.101 CHOICE AMF Paging Target IE Semantics: The AMF paging target is either an NG-RAN node identity or a TAI as specified in TS 38.300 [8].
9.3.1.5 Global RAN Node ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NG-RAN node (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.6 Global gNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a gNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.6 gNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE contained in the NR CGI IE of each cell served by the gNB.
9.3.1.8 Global ng-eNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an ng-eNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.8 Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 20 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Short Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 18 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Long Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 21 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.57 Global N3IWF ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an N3IWF.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

8.3.3 UE Context Release (AMF initiated) 8.3.3.2 Successful Operation If the PDU Session Resource List IE is included in the UE CONTEXT RELEASE COMPLETE message, the AMF shall handle this information as specified in TS 23.502 [10].
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.2.6 PDU Session Resource Release Response Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the PDU Session Resource Release Response Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.21.

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

section_list.name: UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to provide UE Context information changes to the NG-RAN node.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2]. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the New AMF UE NGAP ID IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall use the received value for future signalling with the AMF. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.4 Abnormal Conditions If the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message including the New AMF UE NGAP ID IE is received after the NG-RAN node has initiated another class 1 NGAP EP, the NG-RAN node shall be prepared to receive the response message containing an AMF UE NGAP ID with the value received in the New AMF UE NGAP ID IE.
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority - Section Description: This IE contains the service priority as defined in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 256 as the lowest priority 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the RAN Paging Priority IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node may use it to determine a priority for paging the UE in RRC_INACTIVE state.

9.3.1.87 Security Key - Section Description: This IE is used to apply security in the NG-RAN for different scenarios as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key IE Semantics: Key material for NG-RAN node or Next Hop Key as defined in TS 33.501 [13] 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation Upon receipt of the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message the NG-RAN node shall - store the received Security Key IE and, if the NG-RAN node is required to activate security for the UE, take this security key into use. - store the UE Security Capabilities IE and take them into use together with the received keys according to TS 33.501 [13]. - store the Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority IE and use it as defined in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.61 Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority - Section Description: This IE is used to define local configuration for RRM strategies such as camp priorities in Idle mode and control of inter-RAT/inter-frequency handover in Active mode (see TS 23.501 [9]). 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation Upon receipt of the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message the NG-RAN node shall - store the received Security Key IE and, if the NG-RAN node is required to activate security for the UE, take this security key into use. - store the UE Security Capabilities IE and take them into use together with the received keys according to TS 33.501 [13]. - store the Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority IE and use it as defined in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per UE which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and a subscription parameter provided by the AMF to the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall - replace the previously provided UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate by the received UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate in the UE context; - use the received UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate for all Non-GBR QoS flows for the concerned UE as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.86 UE Security Capabilities - Section Description: This IE defines the supported algorithms for encryption and integrity protection in the UE. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation Upon receipt of the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message the NG-RAN node shall - store the received Security Key IE and, if the NG-RAN node is required to activate security for the UE, take this security key into use. - store the UE Security Capabilities IE and take them into use together with the received keys according to TS 33.501 [13]. - store the Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority IE and use it as defined in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EEA0, "first bit" – 128-EEA1, "second bit" – 128-EEA2, "third bit" – 128-EEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EIA0, "first bit" – 128-EIA1, "second bit" – 128-EIA2, "third bit" – 128-EIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].
├─Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE

9.3.1.15 Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for e.g. RRC_INACTIVE configuration. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store this information in the UE context and use it for e.g. the RRC_INACTIVE state decision and RNA configuration for the UE and RAN paging if any for a UE in RRC_INACTIVE state, as specified in TS 38.300 [8].
9.3.3.23 UE Identity Index Value - Section Description: This IE is used by the NG-RAN node to calculate the Paging Frame as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.3.23 Index Length 10 IE Semantics: Coded as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.1.90 Paging DRX - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging DRX as defined in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].

9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer - Section Description: This IE is used to assist NG-RAN to generate corresponding timer for periodic RNA update for RRC_INACTIVE UEs. 9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer IE Semantics: Bits 5 to 1 represent the binary coded timer value. Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.
9.3.1.23 MICO Mode Indication - Section Description: This IE indicates that the UE is configured with MICO mode by the AMF.
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.

9.3.1.26 Emergency Fallback Indicator - Section Description: The IE indicates emergency service fallback. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the Emergency Fallback Indicator IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, it indicates that the concerned UE context is subject to emergency service fallback as described in TS 23.501 [9] and the NG-RAN node may, if supported, take the appropriate mobility actions taking into account the Emergency Service Target CN IE if provided.

8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the Emergency Fallback Indicator IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, it indicates that the concerned UE context is subject to emergency service fallback as described in TS 23.501 [9] and the NG-RAN node may, if supported, take the appropriate mobility actions taking into account the Emergency Service Target CN IE if provided.

9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2]. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the New AMF UE NGAP ID IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall use the received value for future signalling with the AMF. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.4 Abnormal Conditions If the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message including the New AMF UE NGAP ID IE is received after the NG-RAN node has initiated another class 1 NGAP EP, the NG-RAN node shall be prepared to receive the response message containing an AMF UE NGAP ID with the value received in the New AMF UE NGAP ID IE.
ENUMERATED (Subsequent state transition report, Single RRC connected state report, Cancel report, …)

9.3.1.91 RRC Inactive Transition Report Request - Section Description: This IE is used to request the NG-RAN node to report or stop reporting to the 5GC when the UE enters or leaves RRC_INACTIVE state. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store this information in the UE context and report to the AMF the User Location Information IE and the RRC State IE in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION RESPONSE message. If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message and set to "cancel report", the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, stop reporting to the AMF the RRC state of the UE. If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message and set to "single RRC connected state report", the NG-RAN node shall, if supported and if the UE is in RRC_INACTIVE state, send one subsequent RRC INACTIVE TRANSITION REPORT message to the AMF when the RRC state transitions to RRC_CONNECTED state. If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message and set to "subsequent state transition report", the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, send the RRC INACTIVE TRANSITION REPORT message to the AMF to report the RRC state of the UE when the UE enters or leaves RRC_INACTIVE state.

9.3.3.3 GUAMI - Section Description: This IE indicates the AMF identity. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the New GUAMI IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall replace the previously stored GUAMI as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region.
9.3.3.19 AMF Pointer - Section Description: This IE is used to identify one or more AMF(s) within the AMF Set.

9.3.1.119 CN Assisted RAN Parameters Tuning - Section Description: This IE provides information for assisting in parameters tuning of the NG-RAN node. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the CN Assisted RAN Parameters Tuning IE is included in the UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node may use it as described in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.119 Expected UE Behaviour IE Semantics: This IE may be present in case the Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE IE is not included and is ignored otherwise. 9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.

9.3.1.128 SRVCC Operation Possible - Section Description: This element indicates that both UE and AMF are SRVCC-capable. NG-RAN behaviour on receipt of this IE is specified in TS 23.216 [31]. 9.3.1.128 SRVCC operation possible IE Semantics: The value "Possible" indicates that UE and AMF are SRVCC capable. 8.3.4 UE Context Modification 8.3.4.2 Successful Operation If the SRVCC Operation Possible IE is included in UE CONTEXT MODIFICATION REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store the content of the received SRVCC Operation Possible IE in the UE context and use it as defined in TS 23.216 [31].

9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.16 IP Address IE Semantics: UE's local IP address used to reach the N3IWF 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].
9.3.1.16 Port Number IE Semantics: UDP or TCP source port number if NAT is detected.

section_list.name: HANDOVER REQUIRED
aoa:
This message is sent by the source NG-RAN node to the AMF to request the preparation of resources at the target.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.22 Handover Type - Section Description: This IE indicates which kind of handover was triggered in the source side. 9.3.1.22 Handover Type IE Semantics: Intra5GS: NG-RAN node to NG-RAN node 5GStoEPS: NG-RAN node to eNB EPSto5GS: eNB to NG-RAN node 5GStoUTRA: NG-RAN node to UTRA

9.3.1.2 Cause - Section Description: The purpose of the Cause IE is to indicate the reason for a particular event for the NGAP protocol. 8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.2 Successful Operation The source NG-RAN node initiates the handover preparation by sending the HANDOVER REQUIRED message to the serving AMF. When the source NG-RAN node sends the HANDOVER REQUIRED message, it shall start the timer TNGRELOCprep. The source NG-RAN node shall indicate the appropriate cause value for the handover in the Cause IE. 8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.3 Unsuccessful Operation If there is no response from the AMF to the HANDOVER REQUIRED message before timer TNGRELOCprep expires in the source NG-RAN node, the source NG-RAN node should cancel the Handover Preparation procedure by initiating the Handover Cancel procedure with the appropriate value for the Cause IE. The source NG-RAN node shall ignore any HANDOVER COMMAND message or HANDOVER PREPARATION FAILURE message received after the initiation of the Handover Cancel procedure.

ENUMERATED (Unspecified, TXnRELOCOverall expiry, Successful handover, Release due to NG-RAN generated reason, Release due to 5GC generated reason, Handover cancelled, Partial handover, Handover failure in target 5GC/NG-RAN node or target system, Handover target not allowed, TNGRELOCoverall expiry, TNGRELOCprep expiry, Cell not available, Unknown target ID, No radio resources available in target cell, Unknown local UE NGAP ID, Inconsistent remote UE NGAP ID, Handover desirable for radio reasons, Time critical handover, Resource optimisation handover, Reduce load in serving cell, User inactivity, Radio connection with UE lost, Radio resources not available, Invalid QoS combination, Failure in the radio interface procedure, Interaction with other procedure, Unknown PDU Session ID, Unknown QoS Flow ID, Multiple PDU Session ID Instances, Multiple QoS Flow ID Instances, Encryption and/or integrity protection algorithms not supported, NG intra-system handover triggered, NG inter-system handover triggered, Xn handover triggered, Not supported 5QI value, UE context transfer, IMS voice EPS fallback or RAT fallback triggered, UP integrity protection not possible, UP confidentiality protection not possible, Slice (s) not supported, UE in RRC_INACTIVE state not reachable, Redirection, Resources not available for the slice (s), UE maximum integrity protected data rate reason, Release due to CN-detected mobility, …, N26 interface not available, Release due to pre-emption, Multiple Location Reporting Reference ID Instances)
ENUMERATED (Normal release, Authentication failure, Deregister, Unspecified, …)

ENUMERATED (Transfer syntax error, Abstract syntax error (reject), Abstract syntax error (ignore and notify), Message not compatible with receiver state, Semantic error, Abstract syntax error (falsely constructed message), Unspecified, …)
ENUMERATED (Control processing overload, Not enough user plane processing resources, Hardware failure, O&M intervention, Unknown PLMN, Unspecified, …)
9.3.1.25 Target ID - Section Description: This IE identifies the target for the handover.
9.3.1.5 Global RAN Node ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NG-RAN node (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.6 Global gNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a gNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.6 gNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE contained in the NR CGI IE of each cell served by the gNB.
9.3.1.8 Global ng-eNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an ng-eNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.8 Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 20 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Short Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 18 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Long Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 21 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.57 Global N3IWF ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an N3IWF.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
9.3.1.8 Global ng-eNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an ng-eNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.8 Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 20 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Short Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 18 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Long Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 21 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.3.17 EPS TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an EPS Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.16 EPS TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an EPS Tracking Area Code.
9.3.3.30 LAI - Section Description: This information element is used to uniquely identify a Location Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.30 LAC IE Semantics: 0000 and FFFE not allowed.
9.3.1.25 RNC-ID IE Semantics: If the Extended RNC-ID IE is included in the Target ID IE, the RNC-ID IE shall be ignored. 9.3.1.123 RNC-ID - Section Description: The RNC-ID is used to identify an RNC.

9.3.1.25 Extended RNC-ID IE Semantics: The Extended RNC-ID IE shall be used if the RNC identity has a value larger than 4095. 9.3.1.124 Extended RNC-ID - Section Description: The Extended RNC-ID is used to identify an RNC. 9.3.1.124 Extended RNC-ID IE Semantics: The Extended RNC-ID IE shall be used if the RNC identity has a value larger than 4095.

9.3.1.64 Direct Forwarding Path Availability - Section Description: This IE indicates whether a direct forwarding path is available. 8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.2 Successful Operation If the Direct Forwarding Path Availability IE is included in the HANDOVER REQUIRED message the AMF shall handle it as specified in TS 23.502 [10]. If the Direct Forwarding Path Availability IE is included within the Handover Required Transfer IE of the HANDOVER REQUIRED message the SMF shall handle it as specified in TS 23.502 [10].

9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the HANDOVER REQUIRED message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transparently transfer the Handover Required Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session.

9.2.3.1 Handover Required Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Handover Required Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.14. 8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the HANDOVER REQUIRED message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transparently transfer the Handover Required Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session. If the Direct Forwarding Path Availability IE is included within the Handover Required Transfer IE of the HANDOVER REQUIRED message the SMF shall handle it as specified in TS 23.502 [10].

9.3.1.20 Source to Target Transparent Container - Section Description: This IE is used to transparently pass radio related information from the handover source to the handover target through the core network; it is produced by the source RAN node and is transmitted to the target RAN node. 9.3.1.20 Source to Target Transparent Container IE Semantics: This IE includes a transparent container from the source RAN node to the target RAN node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to the specifications of the target system. Note: In the current version of the specification, this IE may carry either the Source NG-RAN Node to Target NG-RAN Node Transparent Container IE or the Source eNB to Target eNB Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 36.413 [16] or the Source RNC to Target RNC Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 25.413 [28].

section_list.name: HANDOVER COMMAND
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to inform the source NG-RAN node that resources for the handover have been prepared at the target side.
Direction: AMF? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.22 Handover Type - Section Description: This IE indicates which kind of handover was triggered in the source side. 9.3.1.22 Handover Type IE Semantics: Intra5GS: NG-RAN node to NG-RAN node 5GStoEPS: NG-RAN node to eNB EPSto5GS: eNB to NG-RAN node 5GStoUTRA: NG-RAN node to UTRA

9.2.3.2 - NAS Security Parameters from NG-RAN IE - iftoEPSUTRA: This IE shall be present if the Handover Type IE is set to the value "5GStoEPS" or "5GtoUTRA". 9.3.3.26 NAS Security Parameters from NG-RAN - Section Description: This IE provides security related parameters for inter-system handover from NG-RAN to E-UTRAN or from NG-RAN to UTRAN via the eNB to the UE. 9.3.3.26 NAS Security Parameters from NG-RAN IE Semantics: Refers to the N1 mode to S1 mode NAS transparent container IE, the details of the IE definition and the encoding are specified in TS 24.501 [26]. 8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.2 Successful Operation If the NAS Security Parameters from NG-RAN IE is included in the HANDOVER COMMAND message the NG-RAN node shall use it as specified in TS 33.501 [13].

8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.2 Successful Operation When the preparation, including the reservation of resources at the target side is ready, the AMF responds with the HANDOVER COMMAND message to the source NG-RAN node. In case of intra-system handover, the AMF shall include the PDU Session Resource Handover List IE in the HANDOVER COMMAND message.
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.2.3.2 Handover Command Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Handover Command Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.10. 8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.2 Successful Operation In case of intra-system handover, if the HANDOVER COMMAND message contains the DL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE for a given DRB within the Data Forwarding Response DRB List IE in the Handover Command Transfer IE, the source NG-RAN node shall consider that the forwarding of downlink data for this DRB is accepted by the target NG-RAN node. If the HANDOVER COMMAND message contains the UL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE for a given DRB in the Data Forwarding Response DRB List IE within the Handover Command Transfer IE, it means the target NG-RAN node has requested the forwarding of uplink data for this DRB. In case direct data forwarding is applied for inter-system handover, if the Data Forwarding Response E-RAB List IE in the Handover Command Transfer IE is included in the HANDOVER COMMAND message, the source NG-RAN node shall consider that forwarding of downlink data for this E-RAB is accepted by the target eNB. If the HANDOVER COMMAND message contains the UL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE for a given PDU session within the Handover Command Transfer IE, the source NG-RAN node shall consider that the forwarding of uplink data of the QoS flows is accepted by the target NG-RAN node. If the HANDOVER COMMAND message contains the QoS Flow to be Forwarded List IE within the Handover Command Transfer IE for a given PDU session, then the source NG-RAN node should initiate data forwarding for the listed QoS flows over the forwarding tunnel specified in the DL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE as specified in TS 38.300 [8]. If the HANDOVER COMMAND message contains the Additional DL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE within the Handover Command Transfer IE, the source NG-RAN node should initiate data forwarding of the PDU session split in different tunnel and shall use the received UP transport layer information for the forwarding QoS flows associated to it. If the HANDOVER COMMAND message contains the Additional UL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE within the Handover Command Transfer IE, the source NG-RAN node should initiate data forwarding of the PDU session split in different tunnels using the received UP transport layer information.
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.2.3.2 Handover Preparation Unsuccessful Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Handover Preparation Unsuccessful Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.18.

9.3.1.21 Target to Source Transparent Container - Section Description: This IE is used to transparently pass radio related information from the handover target to the handover source through the core network; it is produced by the target RAN node and is transmitted to the source RAN node. 9.3.1.21 Target to Source Transparent Container IE Semantics: This IE includes a transparent container from the target RAN node to the source RAN node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to the specifications of the target system. Note: In the current version of the specification, this IE may carry either the Target NG-RAN Node to Source NG-RAN Node Transparent Container IE or the Target eNB to Source eNB Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 36.413 [16], or the Target RNC to Source RNC Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 25.413 [28]. 8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.2 Successful Operation If the Target to Source Transparent Container IE has been received by the AMF from the handover target then the transparent container shall be included in the HANDOVER COMMAND message.

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.2 Cause - Section Description: The purpose of the Cause IE is to indicate the reason for a particular event for the NGAP protocol. 8.4.1 Handover Preparation 8.4.1.3 Unsuccessful Operation If there is no response from the AMF to the HANDOVER REQUIRED message before timer TNGRELOCprep expires in the source NG-RAN node, the source NG-RAN node should cancel the Handover Preparation procedure by initiating the Handover Cancel procedure with the appropriate value for the Cause IE. The source NG-RAN node shall ignore any HANDOVER COMMAND message or HANDOVER PREPARATION FAILURE message received after the initiation of the Handover Cancel procedure.

When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.

aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to the target NG-RAN node to request the preparation of resources.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.

9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].

9.3.1.22 Handover Type - Section Description: This IE indicates which kind of handover was triggered in the source side. 9.3.1.22 Handover Type IE Semantics: Intra5GS: NG-RAN node to NG-RAN node 5GStoEPS: NG-RAN node to eNB EPSto5GS: eNB to NG-RAN node 5GStoUTRA: NG-RAN node to UTRA

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per UE which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and a subscription parameter provided by the AMF to the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows.

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.15 Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for e.g. RRC_INACTIVE configuration. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation If the Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE IE is included in the HANDOVER REQUEST message, the target NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store this information in the UE context and use it for e.g. the RRC_INACTIVE state decision and RNA configuration for the UE and RAN paging if any for a UE in RRC_INACTIVE state, as specified in TS 38.300 [8].

9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer - Section Description: This IE is used to assist NG-RAN to generate corresponding timer for periodic RNA update for RRC_INACTIVE UEs. 9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer IE Semantics: Bits 5 to 1 represent the binary coded timer value. Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.

9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.86 UE Security Capabilities - Section Description: This IE defines the supported algorithms for encryption and integrity protection in the UE.

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EEA0, "first bit" – 128-EEA1, "second bit" – 128-EEA2, "third bit" – 128-EEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EIA0, "first bit" – 128-EIA1, "second bit" – 128-EIA2, "third bit" – 128-EIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation Upon receiving the PDU Session Resource Setup List IE contained in the HANDOVER REQUEST message, the target NG-RAN node shall behave the same as defined in the PDU Session Resource Setup procedure. The target NG-RAN node shall report to the AMF in the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message the result for each PDU session resource requested to be setup. In particular, for each PDU session resource successfully setup, it shall include the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE containing the following information: - The list of QoS flows which have been successfully established in the QoS Flow Setup Response List IE. - The Data Forwarding Accepted IE if the data forwarding for the QoS flow is accepted. - The list of QoS flows which have failed to be established, if any, in the QoS Flow Failed to Setup List IE. - The UP transport layer information to be used for the PDU session. - The security result associated to the PDU session.
