Value '1' indicates 'should be traced'. Value '0' indicates 'should not be traced'.

9.3.1.54 Masked IMEISV - Section Description: This IE contains the IMEISV value with a mask, to identify a terminal model without identifying an individual Mobile Equipment. 9.3.1.54 Masked IMEISV IE Semantics: Coded as the International Mobile station Equipment Identity and Software Version Number (IMEISV) defined in TS 23.003 [23] with the last 4 digits of the SNR masked by setting the corresponding bits to 1. The first to fourth bits correspond to the first digit of the IMEISV, the fifth to eighth bits correspond to the second digit of the IMEISV, and so on. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation If the Masked IMEISV IE is contained in the HANDOVER REQUEST message the target NG-RAN node shall, if supported, use it to determine the characteristics of the UE for subsequent handling.

9.3.1.20 Source to Target Transparent Container - Section Description: This IE is used to transparently pass radio related information from the handover source to the handover target through the core network; it is produced by the source RAN node and is transmitted to the target RAN node. 9.3.1.20 Source to Target Transparent Container IE Semantics: This IE includes a transparent container from the source RAN node to the target RAN node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to the specifications of the target system. Note: In the current version of the specification, this IE may carry either the Source NG-RAN Node to Target NG-RAN Node Transparent Container IE or the Source eNB to Target eNB Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 36.413 [16] or the Source RNC to Target RNC Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 25.413 [28]. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the UE History Information IE, which is included within the Source to Target Transparent Container IE of the HANDOVER REQUEST message, the target NG-RAN node shall collect the information defined as mandatory in the UE History Information IE and shall, if supported, collect the information defined as optional in the UE History Information IE, for as long as the UE stays in one of its cells, and store the collected information to be used for future handover preparations.

9.3.1.85 Mobility Restriction List - Section Description: This IE defines roaming or access restrictions for subsequent mobility action for which the NG-RAN provides information about the target of the mobility action towards the UE, e.g., handover, or for SCG selection during dual connectivity operation or for assigning proper RNAs. NG-RAN behaviour upon receiving this IE is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation The target NG-RAN node shall use the information in the Mobility Restriction List IE if present in the HANDOVER REQUEST message to - determine a target for subsequent mobility action for which the target NG-RAN node provides information about the target of the mobility action towards the UE; - select a proper SCG during dual connectivity operation; - assign proper RNA(s) for the UE when moving the UE to RRC_INACTIVE state. If the Mobility Restriction List IE is not contained in the HANDOVER REQUEST message, the target NG-RAN node shall consider that no roaming and no access restriction apply to the UE. The target NG-RAN node shall also consider that no roaming and no access restriction apply to the UE when: - one of the QoS flows includes a particular ARP value (TS 23.501 [9]). 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.4 Abnormal Conditions If the target NG-RAN node receives a HANDOVER REQUEST message which does not contain the Mobility Restriction List IE, and the serving PLMN cannot be determined otherwise by the NG-RAN node, the target NG-RAN node shall reject the procedure using the HANDOVER FAILURE message. If the target NG-RAN node receives a HANDOVER REQUEST message containing the Mobility Restriction List IE, and the serving PLMN indicated is not supported by the target cell, the target NG-RAN node shall reject the procedure using the HANDOVER FAILURE message.

Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.76 Location Reporting Reference ID - Section Description: This IE contains the Location Reporting Reference ID.
│  ├─Location Reporting Reference ID to be Cancelled

9.3.1.65 - Location Reporting Reference ID to be Cancelled IE - ifEventTypeisStopUEPresinAoI: This IE shall be present if the Event Type IE is set to "stop UE presence in the area of interest". 9.3.1.76 Location Reporting Reference ID - Section Description: This IE contains the Location Reporting Reference ID.
ENUMERATED (Subsequent state transition report, Single RRC connected state report, Cancel report, …)

9.3.1.91 RRC Inactive Transition Report Request - Section Description: This IE is used to request the NG-RAN node to report or stop reporting to the 5GC when the UE enters or leaves RRC_INACTIVE state. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the HANDOVER REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store this information in the UE context. If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the HANDOVER REQUEST message and set to "subsequent state transition report", the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, send the RRC INACTIVE TRANSITION REPORT message to the AMF to report the RRC state of the UE when the UE enters or leaves RRC_INACTIVE state.
9.3.3.3 GUAMI - Section Description: This IE indicates the AMF identity.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region.
9.3.3.19 AMF Pointer - Section Description: This IE is used to identify one or more AMF(s) within the AMF Set.

9.3.1.116 Redirection for Voice EPS Fallback - Section Description: This IE is used to indicate that the AMF and the UE support the redirection for voice for EPS Fallback. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation If the Redirection for Voice EPS Fallback IE is included in the HANDOVER REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store it and use it in a subsequent decision of EPS fallback for voice as specified in TS 23.502 [10].

9.3.1.119 CN Assisted RAN Parameters Tuning - Section Description: This IE provides information for assisting in parameters tuning of the NG-RAN node. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation If the CN Assisted RAN Parameters Tuning IE is included in the HANDOVER REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node may use it as described in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.119 Expected UE Behaviour IE Semantics: This IE may be present in case the Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE IE is not included and is ignored otherwise. 9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.

9.3.1.128 SRVCC Operation Possible - Section Description: This element indicates that both UE and AMF are SRVCC-capable. NG-RAN behaviour on receipt of this IE is specified in TS 23.216 [31]. 9.3.1.128 SRVCC operation possible IE Semantics: The value "Possible" indicates that UE and AMF are SRVCC capable. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation If the SRVCC Operation Possible IE is included in the HANDOVER REQUEST message, the target NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store the content of the received SRVCC Operation Possible IE in the UE context and use it as defined in TS 23.216 [31].

section_list.name: HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE
aoa:
This message is sent by the target NG-RAN node to inform the AMF about the prepared resources at the target.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].

9.2.3.5 RAN UE NGAP ID IE Semantics: Allocated at the target NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation In case of intra-system handover, if the target NG-RAN node accepts the uplink data forwarding for at least one QoS flow for which the UL Forwarding IE is set to "UL forwarding proposed", it may include the UL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE in the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE for the PDU session within the PDU Session Resource Admitted List IE of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message.

9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transfer transparently the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE or Handover Resource Allocation Unsuccessful Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session.

9.2.3.5 Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.11. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation Upon receiving the PDU Session Resource Setup List IE contained in the HANDOVER REQUEST message, the target NG-RAN node shall behave the same as defined in the PDU Session Resource Setup procedure. The target NG-RAN node shall report to the AMF in the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message the result for each PDU session resource requested to be setup. In particular, for each PDU session resource successfully setup, it shall include the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE containing the following information: - The list of QoS flows which have been successfully established in the QoS Flow Setup Response List IE. - The Data Forwarding Accepted IE if the data forwarding for the QoS flow is accepted. - The list of QoS flows which have failed to be established, if any, in the QoS Flow Failed to Setup List IE. - The UP transport layer information to be used for the PDU session. - The security result associated to the PDU session. Upon reception of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transfer transparently the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE or Handover Resource Allocation Unsuccessful Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session. If the HANDOVER REQUEST message contains the Data Forwarding Not Possible IE associated with a given PDU session within the Handover Request Transfer IE set to "data forwarding not possible", the target NG-RAN node may not include the DL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE and for intra-system handover the Data Forwarding Response DRB List IE within the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE in the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message for that PDU session. In case of intra-system handover, if the target NG-RAN node accepts the downlink data forwarding for at least one QoS flow for which the DL Forwarding IE is set to "DL forwarding proposed", it may include the DL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE in the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE as forwarding tunnel for the QoS flows listed in the QoS Flow Setup Response List IE of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message. In case of intra-system handover, if the target NG-RAN node accepts the uplink data forwarding for at least one QoS flow for which the UL Forwarding IE is set to "UL forwarding proposed", it may include the UL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE in the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE for the PDU session within the PDU Session Resource Admitted List IE of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message. In case of intra-system handover, for each PDU session for which the Additional DL UP TNL Information for HO List IE is included in the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the SMF shall consider the included Additional DL NG-U UP TNL Information IE as the downlink termination point for the associated flows indicated in the Additional QoS Flow Setup Response List IE for this PDU session split in different tunnels and shall consider the Additional DL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE, if included, as the forwarding tunnel associated to these QoS flows. In case of intra-system handover, for each PDU session for which the Additional UL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE is included in the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the SMF shall consider it as the termination points for the uplink forwarding tunnels for this PDU session split in different tunnels. In case of intra-system handover, if the target NG-RAN node accepts the data forwarding for a successfully configured DRB, the target NG-RAN node may include the DL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE for the DRB within the Data Forwarding Response DRB List IE within Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message. If the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message contains the UL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE for a given DRB in the Data Forwarding Response DRB List IE within the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE, it indicates the target NG-RAN node has requested the forwarding of uplink data for the DRB. In case of inter-system handover from E-UTRAN, if the PDU Session Resource Setup Request Transfer IE contains the Direct Forwarding Path Availability IE set to "direct path available", the target NG-RAN node shall, if supported, and if it accepts downlink data forwarding for the QoS flows mapped to an E-RAB of an admitted PDU session, include the DL Forwarding UP TNL Information IE in the Data Forwarding Response E-RAB List IE in the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE in the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message for that mapped E-RAB.
├─PDU Session Resource Failed to Setup List
│  └─PDU Session Resource Failed to Setup Item

9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transfer transparently the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE or Handover Resource Allocation Unsuccessful Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session.

9.2.3.5 Handover Resource Allocation Unsuccessful Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Handover Resource Allocation Unsuccessful Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.19. 8.4.2 Handover Resource Allocation 8.4.2.2 Successful Operation For each PDU session resource which failed to be setup, the Handover Resource Allocation Unsuccessful Transfer IE shall be included in the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message containing a cause value that should be precise enough to enable the SMF to know the reason for the unsuccessful establishment. Upon reception of the HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transfer transparently the Handover Request Acknowledge Transfer IE or Handover Resource Allocation Unsuccessful Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session.

9.3.1.21 Target to Source Transparent Container - Section Description: This IE is used to transparently pass radio related information from the handover target to the handover source through the core network; it is produced by the target RAN node and is transmitted to the source RAN node. 9.3.1.21 Target to Source Transparent Container IE Semantics: This IE includes a transparent container from the target RAN node to the source RAN node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to the specifications of the target system. Note: In the current version of the specification, this IE may carry either the Target NG-RAN Node to Source NG-RAN Node Transparent Container IE or the Target eNB to Source eNB Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 36.413 [16], or the Target RNC to Source RNC Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 25.413 [28].

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

section_list.name: PATH SWITCH REQUEST
aoa:
This message is sent by the NG-RAN node to inform the AMF of the new serving NG-RAN node and to transfer some NG-U DL tunnel termination point(s) to the SMF via the AMF for one or multiple PDU session resources.

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.4 Abnormal Conditions If the AMF receives a PATH SWITCH REQUEST message containing several PDU Session ID IEs (in the PDU Session Resource to be Switched in Downlink List IE) set to the same value, the AMF shall send the PATH SWITCH REQUEST FAILURE message to the NG-RAN node.
│  └─PDU Session Resource to be Switched in Downlink Item

9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation The NG-RAN node initiates the procedure by sending the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message to the AMF. Upon reception of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transparently transfer the Path Switch Request Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.4 Abnormal Conditions If the AMF receives a PATH SWITCH REQUEST message containing several PDU Session ID IEs (in the PDU Session Resource to be Switched in Downlink List IE) set to the same value, the AMF shall send the PATH SWITCH REQUEST FAILURE message to the NG-RAN node.

9.2.3.8 Path Switch Request Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Path Switch Request Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.8. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation The NG-RAN node initiates the procedure by sending the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message to the AMF. Upon reception of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transparently transfer the Path Switch Request Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session. The list of accepted QoS flows shall be included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message within the Path Switch Request Transfer IE. The SMF shall handle this information as specified in TS 23.502 [10]. For each PDU session for which the Additional DL QoS Flow per TNL Information IE is included in the Path Switch Request Transfer IE of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message, the SMF may use each included UP transport layer information as the downlink termination point for the included associated QoS flows for this PDU session split in different tunnels. For each PDU session for which the User Plane Security Information IE is included in the Path Switch Request Transfer IE of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message, the SMF shall behave as specified in TS 33.501 [13] and may send back the Security Indication IE within the Path Switch Request Acknowledge Transfer IE of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message. For each PDU session for which the DL NG-U TNL Information Reused IE set to "true" is included in the Path Switch Request Transfer IE of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message, the SMF shall, if supported, consider that the DL TNL information contained in the DL NG-U UP TNL Information IE has been reused.
└─PDU Session Resource Failed to Setup List
└─PDU Session Resource Failed to Setup Item

9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation The NG-RAN node initiates the procedure by sending the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message to the AMF. Upon reception of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message the AMF shall, for each PDU session indicated in the PDU Session ID IE, transparently transfer the Path Switch Request Transfer IE to the SMF associated with the concerned PDU session. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.4 Abnormal Conditions If the AMF receives a PATH SWITCH REQUEST message containing several PDU Session ID IEs (in the PDU Session Resource to be Switched in Downlink List IE) set to the same value, the AMF shall send the PATH SWITCH REQUEST FAILURE message to the NG-RAN node.

9.2.3.8 Path Switch Request Setup Failed Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Path Switch Request Setup Failed Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.15. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation The list of PDU sessions which failed to be setup, if any, shall be included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message within the Path Switch Request Setup Failed Transfer IE. The AMF shall handle this information as specified in TS 23.502 [10].

section_list.name: PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to inform the NG-RAN node that the path switch has been successfully completed in the 5GC.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.86 UE Security Capabilities - Section Description: This IE defines the supported algorithms for encryption and integrity protection in the UE. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation If the UE Security Capabilities IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall handle it accordingly (TS 33.501 [13]).

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EEA0, "first bit" – 128-EEA1, "second bit" – 128-EEA2, "third bit" – 128-EEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EIA0, "first bit" – 128-EIA1, "second bit" – 128-EIA2, "third bit" – 128-EIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.88 Security Context - Section Description: This IE provides security related parameters to the NG-RAN node which are used to derive security keys for user plane traffic and RRC signalling messages and for security parameter generation for subsequent mobility, see TS 33.501 [13]. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation Upon reception of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message the NG-RAN node shall store the received Security Context IE in the UE context and the NG-RAN node shall use it as specified in TS 33.501 [13].
9.3.1.88 Next Hop Chaining Count IE Semantics: Next Hop Chaining Counter (NCC) defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.88 Next-Hop NH IE Semantics: The NH together with the NCC is used to derive the security configuration as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key - Section Description: This IE is used to apply security in the NG-RAN for different scenarios as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key IE Semantics: Key material for NG-RAN node or Next Hop Key as defined in TS 33.501 [13]

9.3.1.55 New Security Context Indicator - Section Description: This IE indicates that the AMF has activated a new 5G NAS security context as described in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.55 New Security Context Indicator IE Semantics: The NSCI as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation If the New Security Context Indicator IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall use the information as specified in TS 33.501 [13].
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.2.3.9 Path Switch Request Acknowledge Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Path Switch Request Acknowledge Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.9. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation For each PDU session for which the User Plane Security Information IE is included in the Path Switch Request Transfer IE of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST message, the SMF shall behave as specified in TS 33.501 [13] and may send back the Security Indication IE within the Path Switch Request Acknowledge Transfer IE of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message. If the Security Indication IE is included within the Path Switch Request Acknowledge Transfer IE of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall behave as specified in TS 33.501 [13]. If the UL NG-U UP TNL Information IE is included within the Path Switch Request Acknowledge Transfer IE of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall store this information and use it as the uplink termination point for the user plane data for this PDU session. If the Additional NG-U UP TNL Information IE is included within the Path Switch Request Acknowledge Transfer IE of the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall store this information and use the included UL NG-U UP TNL Information IE(s) as the uplink termination point(s) of the user plane data for this PDU session split in different tunnel.

8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation If the PDU Session Resource Released List IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall release the corresponding QoS flows and regard the PDU session(s) indicated in the PDU Session Resource Released List IE as being released. The appropriate cause value for each PDU session released is included in the Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE contained in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message.
9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.2.3.9 Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.20. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation If the PDU Session Resource Released List IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall release the corresponding QoS flows and regard the PDU session(s) indicated in the PDU Session Resource Released List IE as being released. The appropriate cause value for each PDU session released is included in the Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE contained in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message.
9.2.3.9 Allowed NSSAI IE Semantics: Indicates the S-NSSAIs permitted by the network. 9.3.1.31 Allowed NSSAI - Section Description: This IE contains the allowed NSSAI.
9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].
├─Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE

9.3.1.15 Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for e.g. RRC_INACTIVE configuration. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation If the Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store this information in the UE context and use it for e.g. the RRC_INACTIVE state decision and RNA configuration for the UE and RAN paging if any for a UE in RRC_INACTIVE state, as specified in TS 38.300 [8].
9.3.3.23 UE Identity Index Value - Section Description: This IE is used by the NG-RAN node to calculate the Paging Frame as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.3.23 Index Length 10 IE Semantics: Coded as specified in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].
9.3.1.90 Paging DRX - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging DRX as defined in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].

9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer - Section Description: This IE is used to assist NG-RAN to generate corresponding timer for periodic RNA update for RRC_INACTIVE UEs. 9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer IE Semantics: Bits 5 to 1 represent the binary coded timer value. Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.
9.3.1.23 MICO Mode Indication - Section Description: This IE indicates that the UE is configured with MICO mode by the AMF.
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.
ENUMERATED (Subsequent state transition report, Single RRC connected state report, Cancel report, …)

9.3.1.91 RRC Inactive Transition Report Request - Section Description: This IE is used to request the NG-RAN node to report or stop reporting to the 5GC when the UE enters or leaves RRC_INACTIVE state. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store this information in the UE context. If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message and set to "single RRC connected state report" and the UE is in RRC_CONNECTED state, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, send one RRC INACTIVE TRANSITION REPORT message to the AMF to report the RRC state of the UE. If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message and set to "single RRC connected state report" and the UE is in RRC_INACTIVE state, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, send to the AMF one RRC INACTIVE TRANSITION REPORT message plus one subsequent RRC INACTIVE TRANSITION REPORT message when the RRC state transitions to RRC_CONNECTED state. If the RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message and set to "subsequent state transition report", the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, send one RRC INACTIVE TRANSITION REPORT message to the AMF to report the RRC state of the UE and subsequent RRC INACTIVE TRANSITION REPORT messages to report the RRC state of the UE when the UE enters or leaves RRC_INACTIVE state.

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

9.3.1.116 Redirection for Voice EPS Fallback - Section Description: This IE is used to indicate that the AMF and the UE support the redirection for voice for EPS Fallback. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation If the Redirection for Voice EPS Fallback IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store it and use it in a subsequent decision of EPS fallback for voice as specified in TS 23.502 [10].

9.3.1.119 CN Assisted RAN Parameters Tuning - Section Description: This IE provides information for assisting in parameters tuning of the NG-RAN node. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation If the CN Assisted RAN Parameters Tuning IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node may use it as described in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.119 Expected UE Behaviour IE Semantics: This IE may be present in case the Core Network Assistance Information for RRC INACTIVE IE is not included and is ignored otherwise. 9.3.1.93 Expected UE Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.93 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: Included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.

9.3.1.128 SRVCC Operation Possible - Section Description: This element indicates that both UE and AMF are SRVCC-capable. NG-RAN behaviour on receipt of this IE is specified in TS 23.216 [31]. 9.3.1.128 SRVCC operation possible IE Semantics: The value "Possible" indicates that UE and AMF are SRVCC capable. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.2 Successful Operation If the SRVCC Operation Possible IE is included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store the content of the received SRVCC Operation Possible IE in the UE context and use it as defined in TS 23.216 [31].

section_list.name: PATH SWITCH REQUEST FAILURE
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to inform the NG-RAN node that a failure has occurred in the 5GC during the Path Switch Request procedure.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.3 Unsuccessful Operation The NG-RAN node shall release the corresponding QoS flows and regard the PDU session(s) indicated in the PDU Session Resource Released List IE included in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST FAILURE message as being released.

9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID - Section Description: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.4 Abnormal Conditions If the AMF receives a PATH SWITCH REQUEST message containing several PDU Session ID IEs (in the PDU Session Resource to be Switched in Downlink List IE) set to the same value, the AMF shall send the PATH SWITCH REQUEST FAILURE message to the NG-RAN node.

9.2.3.10 Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE Semantics: Containing the PDU session Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE specified in subclause 9.3.4.20. 8.4.4 Path Switch Request 8.4.4.3 Unsuccessful Operation The appropriate cause value for each PDU session released is included in the Path Switch Request Unsuccessful Transfer IE contained in the PATH SWITCH REQUEST FAILURE message.

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.

9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

aoa:

9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.2 Cause - Section Description: The purpose of the Cause IE is to indicate the reason for a particular event for the NGAP protocol.

ENUMERATED (Unspecified, TXnRELOCOverall expiry, Successful handover, Release due to NG-RAN generated reason, Release due to 5GC generated reason, Handover cancelled, Partial handover, Handover failure in target 5GC/NG-RAN node or target system, Handover target not allowed, TNGRELOCoverall expiry, TNGRELOCprep expiry, Cell not available, Unknown target ID, No radio resources available in target cell, Unknown local UE NGAP ID, Inconsistent remote UE NGAP ID, Handover desirable for radio reasons, Time critical handover, Resource optimisation handover, Reduce load in serving cell, User inactivity, Radio connection with UE lost, Radio resources not available, Invalid QoS combination, Failure in the radio interface procedure, Interaction with other procedure, Unknown PDU Session ID, Unknown QoS Flow ID, Multiple PDU Session ID Instances, Multiple QoS Flow ID Instances, Encryption and/or integrity protection algorithms not supported, NG intra-system handover triggered, NG inter-system handover triggered, Xn handover triggered, Not supported 5QI value, UE context transfer, IMS voice EPS fallback or RAT fallback triggered, UP integrity protection not possible, UP confidentiality protection not possible, Slice (s) not supported, UE in RRC_INACTIVE state not reachable, Redirection, Resources not available for the slice (s), UE maximum integrity protected data rate reason, Release due to CN-detected mobility, …, N26 interface not available, Release due to pre-emption, Multiple Location Reporting Reference ID Instances)
ENUMERATED (Normal release, Authentication failure, Deregister, Unspecified, …)

ENUMERATED (Transfer syntax error, Abstract syntax error (reject), Abstract syntax error (ignore and notify), Message not compatible with receiver state, Semantic error, Abstract syntax error (falsely constructed message), Unspecified, …)
ENUMERATED (Control processing overload, Not enough user plane processing resources, Hardware failure, O&M intervention, Unknown PLMN, Unspecified, …)

section_list.name: UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER
aoa:
This message is sent by the source NG-RAN node to transfer the uplink PDCP-SN and HFN receiver status and the downlink PDCP SN and HFN transmitter status during intra 5GC NG-based handover.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF.
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.108 RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container - Section Description: This IE is produced by the source NG-RAN node and is transmitted to the target NG-RAN node. It is used for intra 5GC NG handover. This IE is transparent to the AMF. 8.4.6 Uplink RAN Status Transfer 8.4.6.2 Successful Operation For each DRB for which PDCP-SN and HFN status preservation applies, the source NG-RAN node shall include the DRB ID IE, the UL COUNT Value IE and the DL COUNT Value IE within the DRBs Subject to Status Transfer List IE in the RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container IE of the UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER message.

9.3.1.53 DRB ID - Section Description: This IE contains the DRB ID. 8.4.6 Uplink RAN Status Transfer 8.4.6.2 Successful Operation For each DRB for which PDCP-SN and HFN status preservation applies, the source NG-RAN node shall include the DRB ID IE, the UL COUNT Value IE and the DL COUNT Value IE within the DRBs Subject to Status Transfer List IE in the RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container IE of the UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER message.

9.3.1.108 UL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN of the first missing UL PDCP SDU in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 8.4.6 Uplink RAN Status Transfer 8.4.6.2 Successful Operation For each DRB for which PDCP-SN and HFN status preservation applies, the source NG-RAN node shall include the DRB ID IE, the UL COUNT Value IE and the DL COUNT Value IE within the DRBs Subject to Status Transfer List IE in the RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container IE of the UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER message.

9.3.1.108 Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE Semantics: The IE is used in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. The first bit indicates the status of the SDU after the First Missing UL PDCP SDU. The Nth bit indicates the status of the UL PDCP SDU in position (N + First Missing SDU Number) modulo (1 + the maximum value of the PDCP-SN). 0: PDCP SDU has not been received. 1: PDCP SDU has been received correctly. 8.4.6 Uplink RAN Status Transfer 8.4.6.2 Successful Operation The source NG-RAN node may also include in the UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER message the missing and the received uplink SDUs in the Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE for each DRB for which the source NG-RAN node has accepted the request from the target NG-RAN node for uplink forwarding.

9.3.1.108 UL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN of the first missing UL PDCP SDU in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 8.4.6 Uplink RAN Status Transfer 8.4.6.2 Successful Operation For each DRB for which PDCP-SN and HFN status preservation applies, the source NG-RAN node shall include the DRB ID IE, the UL COUNT Value IE and the DL COUNT Value IE within the DRBs Subject to Status Transfer List IE in the RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container IE of the UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER message.

9.3.1.108 Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE Semantics: The IE is used in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. The first bit indicates the status of the SDU after the First Missing UL PDCP SDU. The Nth bit indicates the status of the UL PDCP SDU in position (N + First Missing SDU Number) modulo (1 + the maximum value of the PDCP-SN). 0: PDCP SDU has not been received. 1: PDCP SDU has been received correctly. 8.4.6 Uplink RAN Status Transfer 8.4.6.2 Successful Operation The source NG-RAN node may also include in the UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER message the missing and the received uplink SDUs in the Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE for each DRB for which the source NG-RAN node has accepted the request from the target NG-RAN node for uplink forwarding.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 8.4.6 Uplink RAN Status Transfer 8.4.6.2 Successful Operation For each DRB for which PDCP-SN and HFN status preservation applies, the source NG-RAN node shall include the DRB ID IE, the UL COUNT Value IE and the DL COUNT Value IE within the DRBs Subject to Status Transfer List IE in the RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container IE of the UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER message.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 8.4.6 Uplink RAN Status Transfer 8.4.6.2 Successful Operation For each DRB for which PDCP-SN and HFN status preservation applies, the source NG-RAN node shall include the DRB ID IE, the UL COUNT Value IE and the DL COUNT Value IE within the DRBs Subject to Status Transfer List IE in the RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container IE of the UPLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER message.
└─Old Associated QoS Flow List - UL End Marker Expected

9.3.1.108 Old Associated QoS Flow List - UL End Marker Expected IE Semantics: Indicates that the source NG-RAN node has initiated QoS flow re-mapping and has not yet received SDAP end markers, as described in TS 38.300 [8]. 9.3.1.99 Associated QoS Flow List - Section Description: This IE indicates the list of QoS flows associated with e.g. a DRB or UP TNL endpoint.
9.3.1.51 QoS Flow Identifier - Section Description: This IE identifies a QoS flow within a PDU Session. The definition and use of the QoS Flow Identifier is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.108 Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE Semantics: The IE is used in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. The first bit indicates the status of the SDU after the First Missing UL PDCP SDU. The Nth bit indicates the status of the UL PDCP SDU in position (N + First Missing SDU Number) modulo (1 + the maximum value of the PDCP-SN). 0: PDCP SDU has not been received. 1: PDCP SDU has been received correctly. 8.4.7 Downlink RAN Status Transfer 8.4.7.2 Successful Operation If the Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE is included for at least one DRB in the RAN Status Transfer Transparent Container IE of the DOWNLINK RAN STATUS TRANSFER message, the target NG-RAN node may use it in a Status Report message sent to the UE over the radio interface.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN.
