section_list.name: PAGING
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF and is used to page a UE in one or several tracking areas.
Direction: AMF ? gNB
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.18 UE Paging Identity - Section Description: This IE represents the Identity with which the UE is paged.
9.3.3.20 5G-S-TMSI - Section Description: This IE is used for security reasons, to hide the identity of a subscriber.
9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region.
9.3.3.19 AMF Pointer - Section Description: This IE is used to identify one or more AMF(s) within the AMF Set.
9.3.3.20 5G-TMSI IE Semantics: 5G-TMSI is unique within the AMF that allocated it.

9.3.1.90 Paging DRX - Section Description: This IE indicates the Paging DRX as defined in TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29]. 8.5.1 Paging 8.5.1.2 Successful Operation If the Paging DRX IE is included in the PAGING message, the NG-RAN node shall use it according to TS 38.304 [12] and TS 36.304 [29].

8.5.1 Paging 8.5.1.2 Successful Operation At the reception of the PAGING message, the NG-RAN node shall perform paging of the UE in cells which belong to tracking areas as indicated in the TAI List for Paging IE.
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
ENUMERATED (PrioLevel1, PrioLevel2, PrioLevel3, PrioLevel4, PrioLevel5, PrioLevel6, PrioLevel7, PrioLevel8, …)

9.3.1.78 Paging Priority - Section Description: This element indicates the paging priority for paging a UE. 9.3.1.78 Paging Priority IE Semantics: Lower value codepoint indicates higher priority. 8.5.1 Paging 8.5.1.2 Successful Operation If the Paging Priority IE is included in the PAGING message, the NG-RAN node may use it according to TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.68 UE Radio Capability for Paging - Section Description: This IE contains paging specific UE Radio Capability information. 8.5.1 Paging 8.5.1.2 Successful Operation If the UE Radio Capability for Paging IE is included in the PAGING message, the NG-RAN node may use it to apply specific paging schemes.
│  ├─UE Radio Capability for Paging of NR
9.3.1.68 UE Radio Capability for Paging of NR IE Semantics: Includes the RRC UERadioPagingInformation message as defined in TS 38.331 [18].
│  └─UE Radio Capability for Paging of E-UTRA
9.3.1.68 UE Radio Capability for Paging of E-UTRA IE Semantics: Includes the RRC UERadioPagingInformation message as defined in TS 36.331 [21].

9.3.3.22 Paging Origin - Section Description: This IE indicates whether Paging is originated due to the PDU sessions from the non-3GPP access. 8.5.1 Paging 8.5.1.2 Successful Operation If the Paging Origin IE is included in the PAGING message, the NG-RAN node shall transfer it to the UE according to TS 38.331 [18] and TS 36.331 [21].
9.3.1.69 Assistance Data for Paging - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for paging optimisation.
9.3.1.70 Assistance Data for Recommended Cells - Section Description: This IE provides assistance information for paging in recommended cells.
9.3.1.71 Recommended Cells for Paging - Section Description: This IE contains the recommended cells for paging. This IE is transparent to the 5GC.

9.3.1.71 Recommended Cell Item IE Semantics: Includes visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.71 Time Stayed in Cell IE Semantics: This is included for visited cells and indicates the time a UE stayed in a cell in seconds. If the UE stays in a cell more than 4095 seconds, this IE is set to 4095.
9.3.1.72 Paging Attempt Information - Section Description: This IE includes information related to the paging count over NG.
9.3.1.72 Paging Attempt Count IE Semantics: Paging attempt count (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.72 Intended Number of Paging Attempts IE Semantics: Intended number of paging attempts (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.72 Next Paging Area Scope IE Semantics: Indicates whether the paging area scope will change or not at next paging attempt. Usage specified in TS 38.300 [8].

section_list.name: INITIAL UE MESSAGE
aoa:
This message is sent by the NG-RAN node to transfer the initial layer 3 message to the AMF over the NG interface.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node. 8.3.1 Initial Context Setup 8.3.1.1 General The purpose of the Initial Context Setup procedure is to establish the necessary overall initial UE context at the NG-RAN node, when required, including PDU session context, the Security Key, Mobility Restriction List, UE Radio Capability and UE Security Capabilities, etc. The AMF may initiate the Initial Context Setup procedure if a UE-associated logical NG-connection exists for the UE or if the AMF has received the RAN UE NGAP ID IE in an INITIAL UE MESSAGE message or if the NG-RAN node has already initiated a UE-associated logical NG-connection by sending an INITIAL UE MESSAGE message via another NG interface instance. The procedure uses UE-associated signalling. 8.3.1 Initial Context Setup 8.3.1.2 Successful Operation The NG-RAN node shall use the AMF UE NGAP ID IE and RAN UE NGAP ID IE received in the INITIAL CONTEXT SETUP REQUEST message as identification of the logical connection even if the RAN UE NGAP ID IE had been allocated in an INITIAL UE MESSAGE message sent over a different NG interface instance. 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.1 General The Downlink NAS Transport procedure is used when the AMF only needs to send a NAS message transparently via the NG-RAN node to the UE, and a UE-associated logical NG-connection exists for the UE or the AMF has received the RAN UE NGAP ID IE in an INITIAL UE MESSAGE message or if the NG-RAN node has already initiated a UE-associated logical NG-connection by sending an INITIAL UE MESSAGE message via another NG interface instance. 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.2 Successful Operation The NG-RAN node shall use the AMF UE NGAP ID IE and RAN UE NGAP ID IE received in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message as identification of the logical connection even if the RAN UE NGAP ID IE had been allocated in an INITIAL UE MESSAGE message sent over a different NG interface instance.

9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains a 5GC - UE or UE - 5GC message that is transferred without interpretation in the NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU IE Semantics: The content is defined in TS 24.501 [26].
9.3.1.16 User Location Information - Section Description: This IE is used to provide location information of the UE.
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area. 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.16 Age of Location IE Semantics: Indicates the UTC time when the location information was generated. 9.3.1.75 Time Stamp - Section Description: This IE contains UTC time information. 9.3.1.75 Time Stamp IE Semantics: Encoded in the same format as the first four octets of the 64-bit timestamp format as defined in section 6 of IETF RFC 5905 [25].
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).

9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area. 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.16 Age of Location IE Semantics: Indicates the UTC time when the location information was generated. 9.3.1.75 Time Stamp - Section Description: This IE contains UTC time information. 9.3.1.75 Time Stamp IE Semantics: Encoded in the same format as the first four octets of the 64-bit timestamp format as defined in section 6 of IETF RFC 5905 [25].
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation In case of network sharing, the selected PLMN is indicated by the PLMN Identity IE within the TAI IE included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).

9.3.1.16 IP Address IE Semantics: UE's local IP address used to reach the N3IWF 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].
9.3.1.16 Port Number IE Semantics: UDP or TCP source port number if NAT is detected.
ENUMERATED (emergency, highPriorityAccess, mt-Access, mo-Signalling, mo-Data, mo-VoiceCall, mo-VideoCall, mo-SMS, mps-PriorityAccess, mcs-PriorityAccess, …, notAvailable)

9.3.1.111 RRC Establishment Cause - Section Description: This IE indicates the reason for RRC Connection Establishment as received from the UE in the EstablishmentCause defined in TS 38.331 [18] and TS 36.331 [21], or the reason for RRC Connection Resume as received from the UE in the ResumceCause defined in TS 38.331 [18]. 9.3.1.111 RRC Establishment Cause IE Semantics: The notAvailable value is used in case the UE is re-establishing an RRC connection but there is fallback to RRC connection establishment as described in [18], or the ResumceCause received from the UE does not map to any other value of the RRC Establishment Cause IE.

9.3.3.20 5G-S-TMSI - Section Description: This IE is used for security reasons, to hide the identity of a subscriber. 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation When the NG-RAN node has received from the radio interface the 5G-S-TMSI IE, it shall include it in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message.

9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region. 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation If the AMF Set ID IE is included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message this indicates that the message is a rerouted message and the AMF shall, if supported, use the IE as described in TS 23.502 [10]. 8.6.5 Reroute NAS Request 8.6.5.2 Successful Operation The AMF initiates the procedure by sending a REROUTE NAS REQUEST message to the NG-RAN node. The NG-RAN node shall, if supported, reroute the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message to an AMF indicated by the AMF Set ID IE as described in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.3.19 AMF Pointer - Section Description: This IE is used to identify one or more AMF(s) within the AMF Set.
9.3.3.20 5G-TMSI IE Semantics: 5G-TMSI is unique within the AMF that allocated it.

9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region. 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation If the AMF Set ID IE is included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message this indicates that the message is a rerouted message and the AMF shall, if supported, use the IE as described in TS 23.502 [10]. 8.6.5 Reroute NAS Request 8.6.5.2 Successful Operation The AMF initiates the procedure by sending a REROUTE NAS REQUEST message to the NG-RAN node. The NG-RAN node shall, if supported, reroute the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message to an AMF indicated by the AMF Set ID IE as described in TS 23.501 [9].

8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation If the UE Context Request IE is included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message the AMF shall trigger an Initial Context Setup procedure towards the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.31 Allowed NSSAI - Section Description: This IE contains the allowed NSSAI. 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation If the Allowed NSSAI IE is included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message the AMF shall use the IE as defined in TS 23.502 [10]. 8.6.5 Reroute NAS Request 8.6.5.2 Successful Operation If the Allowed NSSAI IE is included in the REROUTE NAS REQUEST message, then the NG-RAN node shall propagate it in the rerouted INITIAL UE MESSAGE message as defined in TS 23.502 [10].
9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].

9.3.3.27 Source to Target AMF Information Reroute - Section Description: This IE is used to transparently pass information provided by NSSF from the source AMF to the target AMF through the NG-RAN node; it is produced by the source core network node and is transmitted to the target core network node. 8.6.1 Initial UE Message 8.6.1.2 Successful Operation If the Source to Target AMF Information Reroute IE is included in the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message the AMF shall use the IE as defined in TS 23.502 [10]. 8.6.5 Reroute NAS Request 8.6.5.2 Successful Operation If the Source to Target AMF Information Reroute IE is included in the REROUTE NAS REQUEST message, then the NG-RAN node shall propagate it in the rerouted INITIAL UE MESSAGE message as defined in TS 23.502 [10].

9.3.3.27 Configured NSSAI IE Semantics: The maximum number of S-NSSAI in Configured NSSAI is 16.This IE contains optional mapping S-NSSAI. When present, this IE shall be transmitted transparent from the source Core network node to the target Core network node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to description in TS 29.531 [30]

9.3.3.27 Rejected NSSAI in PLMN IE Semantics: This IE contain the rejected NSSAI(s) in the PLMN. When present, this IE shall be transmitted transparent from the source Core network node to the target Core network node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to description in TS 29.531 [30].

9.3.3.27 Rejected NSSAI in TA IE Semantics: This IE contain the rejected NSSAI(s) in the TA. When present, this IE shall be transmitted transparent from the source Core network node to the target Core network node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to description in TS 29.531 [30].

section_list.name: DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF and is used for carrying NAS information over the NG interface.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2]. 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.2 Successful Operation The AMF initiates the procedure by sending a DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message to the NG-RAN node. If the UE-associated logical NG-connection is not established, the AMF shall allocate a unique AMF UE NGAP ID to be used for the UE and include that in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message; by receiving the AMF UE NGAP ID IE in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message, the NG-RAN node establishes the UE-associated logical NG-connection. The NG-RAN node shall use the AMF UE NGAP ID IE and RAN UE NGAP ID IE received in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message as identification of the logical connection even if the RAN UE NGAP ID IE had been allocated in an INITIAL UE MESSAGE message sent over a different NG interface instance.

9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node. 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.2 Successful Operation The NG-RAN node shall use the AMF UE NGAP ID IE and RAN UE NGAP ID IE received in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message as identification of the logical connection even if the RAN UE NGAP ID IE had been allocated in an INITIAL UE MESSAGE message sent over a different NG interface instance.

9.3.3.21 AMF Name - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify the AMF (see TS 38.300 [8]). It may also be used as a human readable name of the AMF. 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.2 Successful Operation If the Old AMF IE is included in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message, the NG-RAN node shall consider that this UE-associated logical NG-connection was redirected to this AMF from another AMF identified by the Old AMF IE.

9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority - Section Description: This IE contains the service priority as defined in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.15 RAN Paging Priority IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 256 as the lowest priority 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.2 Successful Operation If the RAN Paging Priority IE is included in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message, the NG-RAN node may use it to determine a priority for paging the UE in RRC_INACTIVE state.

9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains a 5GC - UE or UE - 5GC message that is transferred without interpretation in the NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU IE Semantics: The content is defined in TS 24.501 [26].

9.3.1.85 Mobility Restriction List - Section Description: This IE defines roaming or access restrictions for subsequent mobility action for which the NG-RAN provides information about the target of the mobility action towards the UE, e.g., handover, or for SCG selection during dual connectivity operation or for assigning proper RNAs. NG-RAN behaviour upon receiving this IE is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.2 Successful Operation If the Mobility Restriction List IE is contained in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message, the NG-RAN node shall overwrite any previously stored mobility restriction information in the UE context. The NG-RAN node shall use the information in the Mobility Restriction List IE if present in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message to: - determine a target for subsequent mobility action for which the NG-RAN node provides information about the target of the mobility action towards the UE; - select a proper SCG during dual connectivity operation; - assign proper RNA(s) for the UE when moving the UE to RRC_INACTIVE state. If the Mobility Restriction List IE is not contained in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message and there is no previously stored mobility restriction information, the NG-RAN node shall consider that no roaming and no access restriction apply to the UE.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).

9.3.1.85 Equivalent PLMNs IE Semantics: Allowed PLMNs in addition to Serving PLMN. This list corresponds to the list of "equivalent PLMNs" as defined in TS 24.501 [26]. This list is part of the roaming restriction information. Roaming restrictions apply to PLMNs other than the Serving PLMN and Equivalent PLMNs.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.85 RAT Restrictions IE Semantics: This IE contains RAT restriction related information as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).

9.3.1.85 RAT Restriction Information IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a RAT. If a bit is set to "1", the respective RAT is restricted for the UE. If a bit is set to "0", the respective RAT is not restricted for the UE. Bits 3-7 reserved for future use.

9.3.1.85 Extended RAT Restriction Information IE Semantics: If this IE is included, the RAT Restriction Information IE is ignored. 9.3.1.126 Extended RAT Restriction Information - Section Description: This IE provides RAT restrictions as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.126 Primary RAT Restriction IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a RAT. If a bit is set to "1", the respective RAT is restricted for the UE. If a bit is set to "0", the respective RAT is not restricted for the UE. Bits 3-7 reserved for future use. The Primary RAT is the RAT used in the access cell, or target cell.
BIT STRING { e-UTRA (0), nR (1), e-UTRA-unlicensed (2), nR-unlicensed (3)} (SIZE (8, …))

9.3.1.126 Secondary RAT Restriction IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a RAT. If a bit is set to "1", the respective RAT is restricted for the UE. If a bit is set to "0", the respective RAT is not restricted for the UE. Bits 4-7 reserved for future use. A Secondary RAT is a RAT used in any cell serving the UE excluding the PCell.
9.3.1.85 Forbidden Area Information IE Semantics: This IE contains Forbidden Area information as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.85 TAC IE Semantics: The TAC of the forbidden TAI. 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
9.3.1.85 Service Area Information IE Semantics: This IE contains Service Area Restriction information as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.85 TAC IE Semantics: The TAC of the allowed TAI. 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.
9.3.1.85 TAC IE Semantics: The TAC of the not-allowed TAI. 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.85 Last E-UTRAN PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Indicates the E-UTRAN PLMN ID from where the UE formerly handed over to 5GS and which is preferred in case of subsequent mobility to EPS. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
│  ├─Core Network Type Restriction for Serving PLMN
9.3.1.85 Core Network Type Restriction for Serving PLMN IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to connect to EPC for the Serving PLMN as specified in TS 23.501 [9].
│  └─Core Network Type Restriction for Equivalent PLMNs

9.3.1.85 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Includes any of the Equivalent PLMNs listed in the Mobility Restriction List IE for which CN Type restriction applies as specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.85 Core Network Type Restriction IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is restricted to connect to EPC or to 5GC for this PLMN.

9.3.1.61 Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority - Section Description: This IE is used to define local configuration for RRM strategies such as camp priorities in Idle mode and control of inter-RAT/inter-frequency handover in Active mode (see TS 23.501 [9]). 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.2 Successful Operation If the Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority IE is included in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, use it as defined in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per UE which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and a subscription parameter provided by the AMF to the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows. 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.2 Successful Operation The UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE should be sent to the NG-RAN node if the AMF has not sent it previously. If it is included in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message, the NG-RAN node shall store the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate in the UE context, and use the received UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate for all Non-GBR QoS flows for the concerned UE as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s
9.2.5.2 Allowed NSSAI IE Semantics: Indicates the S-NSSAIs permitted by the network. 9.3.1.31 Allowed NSSAI - Section Description: This IE contains the allowed NSSAI.
9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].

9.3.1.128 SRVCC Operation Possible - Section Description: This element indicates that both UE and AMF are SRVCC-capable. NG-RAN behaviour on receipt of this IE is specified in TS 23.216 [31]. 9.3.1.128 SRVCC operation possible IE Semantics: The value "Possible" indicates that UE and AMF are SRVCC capable. 8.6.2 Downlink NAS Transport 8.6.2.2 Successful Operation If the SRVCC Operation Possible IE is included in the DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, store the content of the received SRVCC Operation Possible IE in the UE context and use it as defined in TS 23.216 [31].

section_list.name: NAS NON DELIVERY INDICATION
aoa:
This message is sent by the NG-RAN node and is used for reporting the non-delivery of a NAS PDU previously received within a DOWNLINK NAS TRANSPORT message over the NG interface.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains a 5GC - UE or UE - 5GC message that is transferred without interpretation in the NG-RAN node. 9.3.3.4 NAS-PDU IE Semantics: The content is defined in TS 24.501 [26]. 8.6.4 NAS Non Delivery Indication 8.6.4.2 Successful Operation The NG-RAN node initiates the procedure by sending a NAS NON DELIVERY INDICATION message to the AMF. The NG-RAN node shall report the non-delivery of a NAS message by including the non-delivered NAS message within the NAS-PDU IE and an appropriate cause value within the Cause IE, e.g., "NG intra system handover triggered", "NG inter system handover triggered" or "Xn handover triggered".

9.3.1.2 Cause - Section Description: The purpose of the Cause IE is to indicate the reason for a particular event for the NGAP protocol. 8.6.4 NAS Non Delivery Indication 8.6.4.2 Successful Operation The NG-RAN node initiates the procedure by sending a NAS NON DELIVERY INDICATION message to the AMF. The NG-RAN node shall report the non-delivery of a NAS message by including the non-delivered NAS message within the NAS-PDU IE and an appropriate cause value within the Cause IE, e.g., "NG intra system handover triggered", "NG inter system handover triggered" or "Xn handover triggered".

ENUMERATED (Unspecified, TXnRELOCOverall expiry, Successful handover, Release due to NG-RAN generated reason, Release due to 5GC generated reason, Handover cancelled, Partial handover, Handover failure in target 5GC/NG-RAN node or target system, Handover target not allowed, TNGRELOCoverall expiry, TNGRELOCprep expiry, Cell not available, Unknown target ID, No radio resources available in target cell, Unknown local UE NGAP ID, Inconsistent remote UE NGAP ID, Handover desirable for radio reasons, Time critical handover, Resource optimisation handover, Reduce load in serving cell, User inactivity, Radio connection with UE lost, Radio resources not available, Invalid QoS combination, Failure in the radio interface procedure, Interaction with other procedure, Unknown PDU Session ID, Unknown QoS Flow ID, Multiple PDU Session ID Instances, Multiple QoS Flow ID Instances, Encryption and/or integrity protection algorithms not supported, NG intra-system handover triggered, NG inter-system handover triggered, Xn handover triggered, Not supported 5QI value, UE context transfer, IMS voice EPS fallback or RAT fallback triggered, UP integrity protection not possible, UP confidentiality protection not possible, Slice (s) not supported, UE in RRC_INACTIVE state not reachable, Redirection, Resources not available for the slice (s), UE maximum integrity protected data rate reason, Release due to CN-detected mobility, …, N26 interface not available, Release due to pre-emption, Multiple Location Reporting Reference ID Instances)

section_list.name: REROUTE NAS REQUEST
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF in order to request for a rerouting of the INITIAL UE MESSAGE to another AMF.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.2.5.5 NGAP Message IE Semantics: Contains the INITIAL UE MESSAGE

9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region. 8.6.5 Reroute NAS Request 8.6.5.2 Successful Operation The AMF initiates the procedure by sending a REROUTE NAS REQUEST message to the NG-RAN node. The NG-RAN node shall, if supported, reroute the INITIAL UE MESSAGE message to an AMF indicated by the AMF Set ID IE as described in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.31 Allowed NSSAI - Section Description: This IE contains the allowed NSSAI. 8.6.5 Reroute NAS Request 8.6.5.2 Successful Operation If the Allowed NSSAI IE is included in the REROUTE NAS REQUEST message, then the NG-RAN node shall propagate it in the rerouted INITIAL UE MESSAGE message as defined in TS 23.502 [10].
9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].

9.3.3.27 Source to Target AMF Information Reroute - Section Description: This IE is used to transparently pass information provided by NSSF from the source AMF to the target AMF through the NG-RAN node; it is produced by the source core network node and is transmitted to the target core network node. 8.6.5 Reroute NAS Request 8.6.5.2 Successful Operation If the Source to Target AMF Information Reroute IE is included in the REROUTE NAS REQUEST message, then the NG-RAN node shall propagate it in the rerouted INITIAL UE MESSAGE message as defined in TS 23.502 [10].

9.3.3.27 Configured NSSAI IE Semantics: The maximum number of S-NSSAI in Configured NSSAI is 16.This IE contains optional mapping S-NSSAI. When present, this IE shall be transmitted transparent from the source Core network node to the target Core network node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to description in TS 29.531 [30]

9.3.3.27 Rejected NSSAI in PLMN IE Semantics: This IE contain the rejected NSSAI(s) in the PLMN. When present, this IE shall be transmitted transparent from the source Core network node to the target Core network node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to description in TS 29.531 [30].

9.3.3.27 Rejected NSSAI in TA IE Semantics: This IE contain the rejected NSSAI(s) in the TA. When present, this IE shall be transmitted transparent from the source Core network node to the target Core network node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to description in TS 29.531 [30].

section_list.name: NG SETUP REQUEST
aoa:

Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.1.5 Global RAN Node ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NG-RAN node (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.6 Global gNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a gNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.7.1 NG Setup 8.7.1.4 Abnormal Conditions If the NG-RAN node initiates the procedure by sending an NG SETUP REQUEST message including the PLMN Identity IEs and none of the PLMNs provided by the NG-RAN node is identified by the AMF, then the AMF shall reject the NG Setup procedure with an appropriate cause value.

Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.7.1 NG Setup 8.7.1.4 Abnormal Conditions If the NG-RAN node initiates the procedure by sending an NG SETUP REQUEST message including the PLMN Identity IEs and none of the PLMNs provided by the NG-RAN node is identified by the AMF, then the AMF shall reject the NG Setup procedure with an appropriate cause value.
9.2.6.1 Supported TA List IE Semantics: Supported TAs in the NG-RAN node.
9.2.6.1 TAC IE Semantics: Broadcast TAC 9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.2.6.1 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Broadcast PLMN 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC). 8.7.1 NG Setup 8.7.1.4 Abnormal Conditions If the NG-RAN node initiates the procedure by sending an NG SETUP REQUEST message including the PLMN Identity IEs and none of the PLMNs provided by the NG-RAN node is identified by the AMF, then the AMF shall reject the NG Setup procedure with an appropriate cause value.

section_list.name: NG SETUP RESPONSE
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to transfer application layer information for an NG-C interface instance.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.3.21 AMF Name - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify the AMF (see TS 38.300 [8]). It may also be used as a human readable name of the AMF. 8.7.1 NG Setup 8.7.1.2 Successful Operation The AMF shall include the Backup AMF Name IE, if available, in the Served GUAMI List IE in the NG SETUP RESPONSE message. The NG-RAN node shall, if supported, consider the AMF as indicated by the Backup AMF Name IE when performing AMF reselection, as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

8.7.1 NG Setup 8.7.1.2 Successful Operation The AMF shall include the Backup AMF Name IE, if available, in the Served GUAMI List IE in the NG SETUP RESPONSE message. The NG-RAN node shall, if supported, consider the AMF as indicated by the Backup AMF Name IE when performing AMF reselection, as specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.3.3 GUAMI - Section Description: This IE indicates the AMF identity.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.12 AMF Set ID - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify an AMF Set within the AMF Region.
9.3.3.19 AMF Pointer - Section Description: This IE is used to identify one or more AMF(s) within the AMF Set.

9.3.3.21 AMF Name - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify the AMF (see TS 38.300 [8]). It may also be used as a human readable name of the AMF. 8.7.1 NG Setup 8.7.1.2 Successful Operation The AMF shall include the Backup AMF Name IE, if available, in the Served GUAMI List IE in the NG SETUP RESPONSE message. The NG-RAN node shall, if supported, consider the AMF as indicated by the Backup AMF Name IE when performing AMF reselection, as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

8.7.1 NG Setup 8.7.1.2 Successful Operation If the GUAMI Type IE is included in the NG SETUP RESPONSE message, the NG-RAN node shall store the received value and use it for further AMF selection as defined in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.32 Relative AMF Capacity - Section Description: This IE indicates the relative processing capacity of an AMF with respect to the other AMFs in the AMF Set in order to load-balance AMFs within an AMF Set defined in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).

9.3.1.24 S-NSSAI - Section Description: This IE indicates the S-NSSAI as defined in TS 23.003 [23].

9.3.1.3 Criticality Diagnostics - Section Description: The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing. For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.

9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).

9.3.1.6 gNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE contained in the NR CGI IE of each cell served by the gNB.
9.3.1.8 Global ng-eNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an ng-eNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

If the Endpoint IP Address IE, or the Endpoint IP Address IE and the Port Number IE for one or both of the TNL endpoints is included in the AMF TNL Association to Remove List IE, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, initiate removal of the TNL association(s) indicated by the received endpoint IP address(es).If the AMF Name IE is included in the AMF CONFIGURATION UPDATE message, the NG-RAN node shall overwrite the previously stored AMF name and use it to identify the AMF.

8.7.3 AMF Configuration Update 8.7.3.2 Successful Operation If the AMF TNL Association to Add List IE is included in the AMF CONFIGURATION UPDATE message, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, use it to establish the TNL association(s) with the AMF. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14]. 8.7.3 AMF Configuration Update 8.7.3.2 Successful Operation If the AMF CONFIGURATION UPDATE message includes AMF TNL Association to Remove List IE, and the Endpoint IP Address and the Port Number IE for both TNL endpoints of the TNL association(s) is included in the AMF TNL Association to Remove List IE, the NG-RAN node shall, if supported, initiate removal of the TNL association(s) indicated by both received TNL endpoints towards the AMF. 9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

section_list.name: ERROR INDICATION
aoa:
This message is sent by both the NG-RAN node and the AMF to indicate that some error has been detected in the node.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF and AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2]. 8.7.5 Error Indication 8.7.5.2 Successful Operation The ERROR INDICATION message shall contain at least either the Cause IE or the Criticality Diagnostics IE. In case the Error Indication procedure is triggered by utilising UE-associated signalling the AMF UE NGAP ID IE and the RAN UE NGAP ID IE shall be included in the ERROR INDICATION message. If one or both of the AMF UE NGAP ID IE and the RAN UE NGAP ID IE are not correct, the cause shall be set to an appropriate value, e.g., "Unknown local UE NGAP ID" or "Inconsistent remote UE NGAP ID".

9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node. 8.7.5 Error Indication 8.7.5.2 Successful Operation The ERROR INDICATION message shall contain at least either the Cause IE or the Criticality Diagnostics IE. section_list.name: OVERLOAD START
aoa:

Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.1.104 Overload Response - Section Description: This IE indicates the required behaviour of the NG-RAN node in an overload situation. 8.7.7 Overload Start 8.7.7.2 Successful Operation If the Overload Action IE is included the AMF Overload Response IE within the OVERLOAD START message, the NG-RAN node shall use it to identify the related signalling traffic. When the Overload Action IE is set to - "reject RRC connection establishments for non-emergency mobile originated data transfer" (i.e., reject traffic corresponding to RRC cause "mo-data", "mo-SMS", "mo-VideoCall" and "mo-VoiceCall" in TS 38.331 [18] or "mo-data" and "mo-VoiceCall" in TS 36.331 [21]), or - "reject RRC connection establishments for signalling" (i.e., reject traffic corresponding to RRC cause "mo-data", "mo-SMS", "mo-signalling", "mo-VideoCall" and "mo-VoiceCall" in TS 38.331 [18] or "mo-data", "mo-signalling" and "mo-VoiceCall" in TS 36.331 [21]), or - "only permit RRC connection establishments for emergency sessions and mobile terminated services" (i.e., only permit traffic corresponding to RRC cause "emergency" and "mt-Access" in TS 38.331 [18] or in TS 36.331 [21]), or - "only permit RRC connection establishments for high priority sessions and mobile terminated services" (i.e., only permit traffic corresponding to RRC cause "highPriorityAccess", "mps-PriorityAccess", "mcs-PriorityAccess" and "mt-Access" in TS 38.331 [18] or "highPriorityAccess" and "mt-Access" in TS 36.331 [21]),

8.7.7 Overload Start 8.7.7.2 Successful Operation If the Overload Action IE is included the AMF Overload Response IE within the OVERLOAD START message, the NG-RAN node shall use it to identify the related signalling traffic. When the Overload Action IE is set to - "reject RRC connection establishments for non-emergency mobile originated data transfer" (i.e., reject traffic corresponding to RRC cause "mo-data", "mo-SMS", "mo-VideoCall" and "mo-VoiceCall" in TS 38.331 [18] or "mo-data" and "mo-VoiceCall" in TS 36.331 [21]), or - "reject RRC connection establishments for signalling" (i.e., reject traffic corresponding to RRC cause "mo-data", "mo-SMS", "mo-signalling", "mo-VideoCall" and "mo-VoiceCall" in TS 38.331 [18] or "mo-data", "mo-signalling" and "mo-VoiceCall" in TS 36.331 [21]), or - "only permit RRC connection establishments for emergency sessions and mobile terminated services" (i.e., only permit traffic corresponding to RRC cause "emergency" and "mt-Access" in TS 38.331 [18] or in TS 36.331 [21]), or - "only permit RRC connection establishments for high priority sessions and mobile terminated services" (i.e., only permit traffic corresponding to RRC cause "highPriorityAccess", "mps-PriorityAccess", "mcs-PriorityAccess" and "mt-Access" in TS 38.331 [18] or "highPriorityAccess" and "mt-Access" in TS 36.331 [21]), If the Overload Start NSSAI List IE is included in the OVERLOAD START message, the NG-RAN node shall: - if the Slice Traffic Load Reduction Indication IE is present, reduce the signalling traffic by the indicated percentage for the UE(s) whose requested NSSAI only include S-NSSAI(s) contained in the Overload Start NSSAI List IE, and the signalling traffic indicated as to be reduced by the Overload Action IE in the Slice Overload Response IE if the IE is present, - otherwise ensure that only the signalling traffic from UE(s) whose requested NSSAI includes S-NSSAI(s) other than the ones contained in the Overload Start NSSAI List IE, or the signalling traffic not indicated as to be reduced by the Overload Action IE in the Slice Overload Response IE for the UE(s) if the requested NSSAI matched, is sent to the AMF.

9.3.1.106 Traffic Load Reduction Indication - Section Description: This IE indicates the percentage of the type of traffic relative to the instantaneous incoming rate at the NG-RAN node, as indicated in the Overload Action IE, to be rejected. 8.7.7 Overload Start 8.7.7.2 Successful Operation the NG-RAN node shall: - if the AMF Traffic Load Reduction Indication IE is included in the OVERLOAD START message, reduce the signalling traffic by the indicated percentage, - otherwise ensure that only the signalling traffic not indicated as to be rejected is sent to the AMF.

8.7.7 Overload Start 8.7.7.2 Successful Operation If the Overload Start NSSAI List IE is included in the OVERLOAD START message, the NG-RAN node shall: - if the Slice Traffic Load Reduction Indication IE is present, reduce the signalling traffic by the indicated percentage for the UE(s) whose requested NSSAI only include S-NSSAI(s) contained in the Overload Start NSSAI List IE, and the signalling traffic indicated as to be reduced by the Overload Action IE in the Slice Overload Response IE if the IE is present, - otherwise ensure that only the signalling traffic from UE(s) whose requested NSSAI includes S-NSSAI(s) other than the ones contained in the Overload Start NSSAI List IE, or the signalling traffic not indicated as to be reduced by the Overload Action IE in the Slice Overload Response IE for the UE(s) if the requested NSSAI matched, is sent to the AMF.

section_list.name: UPLINK RAN CONFIGURATION TRANSFER
aoa:
This message is sent by the NG-RAN node in order to transfer RAN configuration information.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.3.6 SON Configuration Transfer - Section Description: This IE contains the configuration information, used by e.g., SON functionality, and additionally includes the NG-RAN node identifier of the destination of this configuration information and the NG-RAN node identifier of the source of this information.
9.3.1.5 Global RAN Node ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NG-RAN node (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.6 Global gNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a gNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.6 gNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE contained in the NR CGI IE of each cell served by the gNB.
9.3.1.8 Global ng-eNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an ng-eNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.8 Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 20 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Short Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 18 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Long Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 21 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.57 Global N3IWF ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an N3IWF.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. section_list.name: WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to request the start or overwrite of the broadcast of a warning message.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.1.35 Message Identifier - Section Description: This IE identifies the warning message. It is set by the AMF and transferred to the UE by the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.35 Message Identifier IE Semantics: This IE is set by the 5GC, transferred to the UE by the NG-RAN node. 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If, in a certain area, broadcast of a warning message is already ongoing and the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with Message Identifier IE and/or Serial Number IE which are different from those in the warning message being broadcast, and if the Concurrent Warning Message Indicator IE is not present, the NG-RAN node shall replace the warning message being broadcast with the newly received one for that area. If the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with a warning message identified by the Message Identifier IE and Serial Number IE and if there are no prior warning messages being broadcast in any of the warning areas indicated in the Warning Area List IE, the NG-RAN node shall broadcast the received warning message for those area(s). If, in a certain area, broadcast of one or more warning messages are already ongoing and the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with a Message Identifier IE and/or Serial Number IE which are different from those in any of the warning messages being broadcast, and if the Concurrent Warning Message Indictor IE is present, the NG-RAN node shall schedule the received warning message for broadcast, for that area. If, in a certain area, broadcast of one or more warning messages are already ongoing and the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with Message Identifier IE and Serial Number IE which correspond to one of the warning messages already being broadcast in that area, the NG-RAN node shall not start a new broadcast or replace an existing one but it shall still reply by sending a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING RESPONSE message which includes the Broadcast Completed Area List IE set according to the ongoing broadcast.

9.3.1.36 Serial Number - Section Description: This IE identifies a particular message from the source and type indicated by the Message Identifier and is altered every time the message with a given Message Identifier is changed. 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If, in a certain area, broadcast of a warning message is already ongoing and the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with Message Identifier IE and/or Serial Number IE which are different from those in the warning message being broadcast, and if the Concurrent Warning Message Indicator IE is not present, the NG-RAN node shall replace the warning message being broadcast with the newly received one for that area. If the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with a warning message identified by the Message Identifier IE and Serial Number IE and if there are no prior warning messages being broadcast in any of the warning areas indicated in the Warning Area List IE, the NG-RAN node shall broadcast the received warning message for those area(s). If, in a certain area, broadcast of one or more warning messages are already ongoing and the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with a Message Identifier IE and/or Serial Number IE which are different from those in any of the warning messages being broadcast, and if the Concurrent Warning Message Indictor IE is present, the NG-RAN node shall schedule the received warning message for broadcast, for that area. If, in a certain area, broadcast of one or more warning messages are already ongoing and the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with Message Identifier IE and Serial Number IE which correspond to one of the warning messages already being broadcast in that area, the NG-RAN node shall not start a new broadcast or replace an existing one but it shall still reply by sending a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING RESPONSE message which includes the Broadcast Completed Area List IE set according to the ongoing broadcast.

9.3.1.37 Warning Area List - Section Description: This IE indicates the areas where the warning message needs to be broadcast or cancelled. 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with a warning message identified by the Message Identifier IE and Serial Number IE and if there are no prior warning messages being broadcast in any of the warning areas indicated in the Warning Area List IE, the NG-RAN node shall broadcast the received warning message for those area(s). If the Warning Area List IE is not included in the WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall broadcast the indicated message in all of the cells within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.48 Emergency Area ID - Section Description: This IE is used to indicate the area which has the emergency impact. 9.3.1.48 Emergency Area ID IE Semantics: Emergency Area ID may consist of several cells. Emergency Area ID is defined by the operator.

9.3.1.49 Repetition Period - Section Description: This IE indicates the periodicity of the warning message to be broadcast. 9.3.1.49 Repetition Period IE Semantics: The unit of value 1 to 217-1 is [second]. 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If the Warning Type IE is included in the WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall broadcast the Primary Notification irrespective of the setting of the Repetition Period IE and the Number of Broadcasts Requested IE, and process the Primary Notification according to TS 36.331 [21] and TS 38.331 [18]. If the Data Coding Scheme IE and the Warning Message Contents IE are both included in the WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall schedule a broadcast of the warning message according to the value of the Repetition Period IE and the Number of Broadcasts Requested IE and process the warning message according to TS 36.331 [21] and TS 38.331 [18].

9.3.1.38 Number of Broadcasts Requested - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of times a message is to be broadcast. 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If the Warning Type IE is included in the WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall broadcast the Primary Notification irrespective of the setting of the Repetition Period IE and the Number of Broadcasts Requested IE, and process the Primary Notification according to TS 36.331 [21] and TS 38.331 [18]. If the Data Coding Scheme IE and the Warning Message Contents IE are both included in the WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall schedule a broadcast of the warning message according to the value of the Repetition Period IE and the Number of Broadcasts Requested IE and process the warning message according to TS 36.331 [21] and TS 38.331 [18].

9.3.1.39 Warning Type - Section Description: This IE indicates types of the disaster. This IE also indicates that a Primary Notification is included. This IE can be used by the UE to differentiate the type of alert according to the type of disaster. 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If the Warning Type IE is included in the WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall broadcast the Primary Notification irrespective of the setting of the Repetition Period IE and the Number of Broadcasts Requested IE, and process the Primary Notification according to TS 36.331 [21] and TS 38.331 [18].
9.2.8.1 Warning Security Information IE Semantics: This IE is not used in the specification. If received, the IE is ignored.

9.3.1.41 Data Coding Scheme - Section Description: This IE identifies the alphabet or coding employed for the message characters and message handling at the UE (it is passed transparently from the 5GC to the UE). 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If the Data Coding Scheme IE and the Warning Message Contents IE are both included in the WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall schedule a broadcast of the warning message according to the value of the Repetition Period IE and the Number of Broadcasts Requested IE and process the warning message according to TS 36.331 [21] and TS 38.331 [18].

9.3.1.42 Warning Message Contents - Section Description: This IE contains user information, e.g., the message with warning contents, and will be broadcast over the radio interface. 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If the Data Coding Scheme IE and the Warning Message Contents IE are both included in the WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall schedule a broadcast of the warning message according to the value of the Repetition Period IE and the Number of Broadcasts Requested IE and process the warning message according to TS 36.331 [21] and TS 38.331 [18].

9.3.1.46 Concurrent Warning Message Indicator - Section Description: This IE indicates to the NG-RAN node that the received warning message is a new message to be scheduled for concurrent broadcast with any other ongoing broadcast of warning messages. 9.3.1.46 Concurrent Warning Message Indicator IE Semantics: This IE is used to identify a PWS type warning system which allows the broadcast of multiple concurrent warning messages over the radio. 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If, in a certain area, broadcast of a warning message is already ongoing and the NG-RAN node receives a WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message with Message Identifier IE and/or Serial Number IE which are different from those in the warning message being broadcast, and if the Concurrent Warning Message Indicator IE is not present, the NG-RAN node shall replace the warning message being broadcast with the newly received one for that area.

9.3.1.112 Warning Area Coordinates - Section Description: This IE contains the affected alert area coordinates of a warning message, and will be broadcast over the radio interface. 8.9.1 Write-Replace Warning 8.9.1.2 Successful Operation If the Warning Area Coordinates IE is included in the WRITE-REPLACE WARNING REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall include this information together with the warning message being broadcast according to TS 36.331 [21] and TS 38.331 [18].

section_list.name: PWS CANCEL REQUEST
aoa:
This message is forwarded by the AMF to the NG-RAN node to cancel an already ongoing broadcast of a warning message.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)

9.3.1.35 Message Identifier - Section Description: This IE identifies the warning message. It is set by the AMF and transferred to the UE by the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.35 Message Identifier IE Semantics: This IE is set by the 5GC, transferred to the UE by the NG-RAN node. 8.9.2 PWS Cancel 8.9.2.2 Successful Operation If the Warning Area List IE is not included in the PWS CANCEL REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall stop broadcasting and discard the warning message identified by the Message Identifier IE and the Serial Number IE in all of the cells in the NG-RAN node. The NG-RAN node shall acknowledge the PWS CANCEL REQUEST message by sending the PWS CANCEL RESPONSE message, with the Message Identifier IE and the Serial Number IE copied from the PWS CANCEL REQUEST message and shall, if there is an area to report where an ongoing broadcast was stopped successfully, include the Broadcast Cancelled Area List IE. If the Cancel-All Warning Messages Indicator IE is present in the PWS CANCEL REQUEST message, then the NG-RAN node shall stop broadcasting and discard all warning messages for the area as indicated in the Warning Area List IE or in all the cells of the NG-RAN node if the Warning Area List IE is not included. The NG-RAN node shall acknowledge the PWS CANCEL REQUEST message by sending the PWS CANCEL RESPONSE message, with the Message Identifier IE and the Serial Number IE copied from the PWS CANCEL REQUEST message and shall, if there is area to report where an ongoing broadcast was stopped successfully, include the Broadcast Cancelled Area List IE with the Number of Broadcasts IE set to 0.

9.3.1.36 Serial Number - Section Description: This IE identifies a particular message from the source and type indicated by the Message Identifier and is altered every time the message with a given Message Identifier is changed. 8.9.2 PWS Cancel 8.9.2.2 Successful Operation If the NG-RAN node receives a PWS CANCEL REQUEST message and broadcast of the warning message identified by the Message Identifier and Serial Number IE is ongoing in an area indicated within the Warning Area List IE, the NG-RAN node shall stop broadcasting the warning message within that area and discard the warning message for that area. If the Warning Area List IE is not included in the PWS CANCEL REQUEST message, the NG-RAN node shall stop broadcasting and discard the warning message identified by the Message Identifier IE and the Serial Number IE in all of the cells in the NG-RAN node.
