This message is sent by the NG-RAN node to inform the AMF that PWS information for some or all cells of the NG-RAN node are available for reloading from the CBC if needed.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE correspond to the ng-eNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.8).
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.5 Global RAN Node ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NG-RAN node (see TS 38.300 [8]).
9.3.1.6 Global gNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a gNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.6 gNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE contained in the NR CGI IE of each cell served by the gNB.
9.3.1.8 Global ng-eNB ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an ng-eNB (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.8 Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 20 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Short Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 18 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.8 Long Macro ng-eNB ID IE Semantics: Equal to the 21 leftmost bits of the E-UTRA Cell Identity IE contained in the E-UTRA CGI IE of each cell served by the ng-eNB.
9.3.1.57 Global N3IWF ID - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an N3IWF.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.11 TAI - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area.

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.3.10 TAC - Section Description: This IE is used to uniquely identify a Tracking Area Code.

9.3.1.48 Emergency Area ID - Section Description: This IE is used to indicate the area which has the emergency impact. 9.3.1.48 Emergency Area ID IE Semantics: Emergency Area ID may consist of several cells. Emergency Area ID is defined by the operator.

9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.3.13 Routing ID - Section Description: This IE is used to identify an LMF within the 5GC.
9.3.3.14 NRPPa-PDU - Section Description: This IE contains an NG-RAN node - LMF or LMF - NG-RAN node message that is transferred without interpretation in the AMF.

section_list.name: TRACE START
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to initiate a trace session for a UE.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.3.1.14 Trace Activation - Section Description: This IE defines parameters related to a trace session activation.

9.3.1.14 NG-RAN Trace ID IE Semantics: This IE is composed of the following: Trace Reference defined in TS 32.422 [11] (leftmost 6 octets, with PLMN information encoded as in 9.3.3.1), and Trace Recording Session Reference defined in TS 32.422 [11] (last 2 octets).

9.3.1.14 Interfaces to Trace IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an NG-RAN node interface: first bit = NG-C, second bit = Xn-C, third bit = Uu, fourth bit = F1-C, fifth bit = E1: other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates 'should be traced'. Value '0' indicates 'should not be traced'.
ENUMERATED (minimum, medium, maximum, minimumWithoutVendorSpecificExtension, mediumWithoutVendorSpecificExtension, maximumWithoutVendorSpecificExtension, …)
9.3.1.14 Trace Depth IE Semantics: Defined in TS 32.422 [11].

9.3.1.14 Trace Collection Entity IP Address IE Semantics: Defined in TS 32.422 [11] 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].

section_list.name: TRACE FAILURE INDICATION
aoa:
This message is sent by the NG-RAN node to indicate that a Trace Start procedure or a Deactivate Trace procedure has failed for a UE.
Direction: NG-RAN node ? AMF
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.
9.2.10.2 NG-RAN Trace ID IE Semantics: As per NG-RAN Trace ID in Trace Activation IE

9.3.1.2 Cause - Section Description: The purpose of the Cause IE is to indicate the reason for a particular event for the NGAP protocol. 8.11.2 Trace Failure Indication 8.11.2.2 Successful Operation The NG-RAN node initiates the procedure by sending a TRACE FAILURE INDICATION message. Upon reception of the TRACE FAILURE INDICATION message, the AMF shall take appropriate actions based on the failure reason indicated by the Cause IE.

ENUMERATED (Unspecified, TXnRELOCOverall expiry, Successful handover, Release due to NG-RAN generated reason, Release due to 5GC generated reason, Handover cancelled, Partial handover, Handover failure in target 5GC/NG-RAN node or target system, Handover target not allowed, TNGRELOCoverall expiry, TNGRELOCprep expiry, Cell not available, Unknown target ID, No radio resources available in target cell, Unknown local UE NGAP ID, Inconsistent remote UE NGAP ID, Handover desirable for radio reasons, Time critical handover, Resource optimisation handover, Reduce load in serving cell, User inactivity, Radio connection with UE lost, Radio resources not available, Invalid QoS combination, Failure in the radio interface procedure, Interaction with other procedure, Unknown PDU Session ID, Unknown QoS Flow ID, Multiple PDU Session ID Instances, Multiple QoS Flow ID Instances, Encryption and/or integrity protection algorithms not supported, NG intra-system handover triggered, NG inter-system handover triggered, Xn handover triggered, Not supported 5QI value, UE context transfer, IMS voice EPS fallback or RAT fallback triggered, UP integrity protection not possible, UP confidentiality protection not possible, Slice (s) not supported, UE in RRC_INACTIVE state not reachable, Redirection, Resources not available for the slice (s), UE maximum integrity protected data rate reason, Release due to CN-detected mobility, …, N26 interface not available, Release due to pre-emption, Multiple Location Reporting Reference ID Instances)
ENUMERATED (Normal release, Authentication failure, Deregister, Unspecified, …)

ENUMERATED (Transfer syntax error, Abstract syntax error (reject), Abstract syntax error (ignore and notify), Message not compatible with receiver state, Semantic error, Abstract syntax error (falsely constructed message), Unspecified, …)
ENUMERATED (Control processing overload, Not enough user plane processing resources, Hardware failure, O&M intervention, Unknown PLMN, Unspecified, …)

section_list.name: DEACTIVATE TRACE
aoa:
This message is sent by the AMF to deactivate a trace session.
Direction: AMF ? NG-RAN node
9.3.1.1 Message Type - Section Description: The Message Type IE uniquely identifies the message being sent. It is mandatory for all messages.
CHOICE (Initiating Message, Successful Outcome, Unsuccessful Outcome, …)
9.3.3.1 AMF UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface, as described in TS 38.401 [2].
9.3.3.2 RAN UE NGAP ID - Section Description: This IE uniquely identifies the UE association over the NG interface within the NG-RAN node.

9.2.10.3 NG-RAN Trace ID IE Semantics: As per NG-RAN Trace ID in Trace Activation IE 8.11.3 Deactivate Trace 8.11.3.2 Successful Operation The AMF initiates the procedure by sending a DEACTIVATE TRACE message to the NG-RAN node as described in TS 32.422 [11]. Upon reception of the DEACTIVATE TRACE message, the NG-RAN node shall stop the trace session for the indicated trace reference in the NG-RAN Trace ID IE.

9.3.1.65 Location Reporting Request Type - Section Description: This IE indicates the type of location request to be handled by the NG-RAN node. 8.12.1 Location Reporting Control 8.12.1.2 Successful Operation If the Area Of Interest List IE is included in the Location Reporting Request Type IE in the LOCATION REPORTING CONTROL message, the NG-RAN node shall store this information and use it to track the UE's presence in the area of interest as defined in TS 23.502 [10].
ENUMERATED (direct, change of serving cell, UE presence in the area of interest, stop change of serving cell, stop UE presence in the area of interest, cancel location reporting for the UE, …)

8.12.1 Location Reporting Control 8.12.1.2 Successful Operation If the Area of Interest List IE is included in the Location Reporting Request Type IE in the LOCATION REPORTING CONTROL message, the NG-RAN node shall store this information and use it to track the UE's presence in the area of interest as defined in TS 23.502 [10].

section_list.name: Criticality Diagnostics
aoa:
The Criticality Diagnostics IE is sent by the NG-RAN node or the AMF when parts of a received message have not been comprehended or were missing, or if the message contained logical errors. When applicable, it contains information about which IEs were not comprehended or were missing.
For further details on how to use the Criticality Diagnostics IE, see clause 10.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Code IE Semantics: Used if Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure, and not within the response message of the same procedure that caused the error.
ENUMERATED (initiating message, successful outcome, unsuccessful outcome)
9.3.1.3 Triggering Message IE Semantics: Used only if the Criticality Diagnostics is part of Error Indication procedure.
9.3.1.3 Procedure Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the Criticality of the Triggering message (Procedure).
9.3.1.3 IE Criticality IE Semantics: Used for reporting the criticality of the triggering IE. The value 'ignore' is not applicable.
9.3.1.3 IE ID IE Semantics: The IE ID of the not understood or missing IE.

section_list.name: Bit Rate
aoa: 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.18 Priority Level IE Semantics: Priority Level is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.1.84 Priority Level - Section Description: This IE indicates the Priority Level for a QoS flow. 9.3.1.84 Priority Level IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 127 as the lowest priority.

9.3.1.18 Packet Error Rate IE Semantics: Packet Error Rate is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. 9.3.1.81 Packet Error Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the Packet Error Rate for a QoS flow.
9.3.1.81 Scalar IE Semantics: The packet error rate is expressed as Scalar x 10-k where k is the Exponent.
9.3.1.18 5QI IE Semantics: Indicates the dynamically assigned 5QI as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.19 Priority Level IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE defines the relative importance of a resource request (see TS 23.501 [9]). Usage: Values are ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e., with 1 as the highest priority and 15 as the lowest priority.
ENUMERATED (shall not trigger pre-emption, may trigger pre-emption, …)

9.3.1.19 Pre-emption Capability IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE indicates the pre-emption capability of the request on other QoS flows (see TS 23.501 [9]). Usage: The QoS flow shall not pre-empt other QoS flows or, the QoS flow may pre-empt other QoS flows. Note: The Pre-emption Capability indicator applies to the allocation of resources for a QoS flow and as such it provides the trigger to the pre-emption procedures/processes of the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.19 Pre-emption Vulnerability IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE indicates the vulnerability of the QoS flow to pre-emption of other QoS flows (see TS 23.501 [9]). Usage: The QoS flow shall not be pre-empted by other QoS flows or the QoS flow may be pre-empted by other QoS flows. Note: The Pre-emption Vulnerability indicator applies for the entire duration of the QoS flow, unless modified and as such indicates whether the QoS flow is a target of the pre-emption procedures/processes of the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.14 Interfaces to Trace IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an NG-RAN node interface: first bit = NG-C, second bit = Xn-C, third bit = Uu, fourth bit = F1-C, fifth bit = E1: other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates 'should be traced'. Value '0' indicates 'should not be traced'.

Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.

9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.

section_list.name: Allocation and Retention Priority
aoa: This IE specifies the relative importance of a QoS flow compared to other QoS flows for allocation and retention of NG-RAN resources.

9.3.1.19 Priority Level IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE defines the relative importance of a resource request (see TS 23.501 [9]). Usage: Values are ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e., with 1 as the highest priority and 15 as the lowest priority.
ENUMERATED (shall not trigger pre-emption, may trigger pre-emption, …)

9.3.1.19 Pre-emption Capability IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE indicates the pre-emption capability of the request on other QoS flows (see TS 23.501 [9]). Usage: The QoS flow shall not pre-empt other QoS flows or, the QoS flow may pre-empt other QoS flows. Note: The Pre-emption Capability indicator applies to the allocation of resources for a QoS flow and as such it provides the trigger to the pre-emption procedures/processes of the NG-RAN node.

9.3.1.19 Pre-emption Vulnerability IE Semantics: Desc.: This IE indicates the vulnerability of the QoS flow to pre-emption of other QoS flows (see TS 23.501 [9]). Usage: The QoS flow shall not be pre-empted by other QoS flows or the QoS flow may be pre-empted by other QoS flows. Note: The Pre-emption Vulnerability indicator applies for the entire duration of the QoS flow, unless modified and as such indicates whether the QoS flow is a target of the pre-emption procedures/processes of the NG-RAN node.

section_list.name: Source to Target Transparent Container
aoa: 9.3.1.20 Source to Target Transparent Container IE Semantics: This IE is used to transparently pass radio related information from the handover source to the handover target through the core network; it is produced by the source RAN node and is transmitted to the target RAN node. This IE includes a transparent container from the source RAN node to the target RAN node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to the specifications of the target system. Note: In the current version of the specification, this IE may carry either the Source NG-RAN Node to Target NG-RAN Node Transparent Container IE or the Source eNB to Target eNB Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 36.413 [16] or the Source RNC to Target RNC Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 25.413 [28].

section_list.name: Target to Source Transparent Container
aoa: 9.3.1.21 Target to Source Transparent Container IE Semantics: This IE is used to transparently pass radio related information from the handover target to the handover source through the core network; it is produced by the target RAN node and is transmitted to the source RAN node. This IE includes a transparent container from the target RAN node to the source RAN node. The octets of the OCTET STRING are encoded according to the specifications of the target system. Note: In the current version of the specification, this IE may carry either the Target NG-RAN Node to Source NG-RAN Node Transparent Container IE or the Target eNB to Source eNB Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 36.413 [16], or the Target RNC to Source RNC Transparent Container IE as defined in TS 25.413 [28].

section_list.name: Security Indication
aoa: This IE contains the user plane integrity protection indication and confidentiality protection indication which indicates the requirements on UP integrity protection and ciphering for corresponding PDU sessions, respectively. Additionally, this IE contains the maximum integrity protected data rate per UE for integrity protection for DRBs.

9.3.1.27 Confidentiality Protection Indication IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP ciphering shall apply, should apply or shall not apply for the concerned PDU session.

section_list.name: Target NG-RAN Node to Source NG-RAN Node Transparent Container
aoa: 9.3.1.30 RRC Container IE Semantics: This IE is produced by the target NG-RAN node and is transmitted to the source NG-RAN node. section_list.name: Concurrent Warning Message Indicator
aoa: 9.3.1.46 Concurrent Warning Message Indicator IE Semantics: This IE indicates to the NG-RAN node that the received warning message is a new message to be scheduled for concurrent broadcast with any other ongoing broadcast of warning messages. This IE is used to identify a PWS type warning system which allows the broadcast of multiple concurrent warning messages over the radio.

section_list.name: Cancel-All Warning Messages Indicator
aoa: 9.3.1.47 Cancel-All Warning Messages Indicator IE Semantics: This IE indicates to the NG-RAN node to stop all already ongoing broadcast of warning messages in the NG-RAN node or in an area.

section_list.name: Repetition Period
aoa: 9.3.1.49 Repetition Period IE Semantics: This IE indicates the periodicity of the warning message to be broadcast. The unit of value 1 to 217-1 is [second].

aoa: 9.3.1.50 PDU Session ID IE Semantics: This IE identifies a PDU Session for a UE. The definition and use of the PDU Session ID is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

aoa: 9.3.1.51 QoS Flow Identifier IE Semantics: This IE identifies a QoS flow within a PDU Session. The definition and use of the QoS Flow Identifier is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

section_list.name: PDU Session Type
aoa: 9.3.1.52 PDU Session Type IE Semantics: This IE indicates the PDU Session Type as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

section_list.name: DRB ID

section_list.name: Masked IMEISV
aoa: 9.3.1.54 Masked IMEISV IE Semantics: This IE contains the IMEISV value with a mask, to identify a terminal model without identifying an individual Mobile Equipment. Coded as the International Mobile station Equipment Identity and Software Version Number (IMEISV) defined in TS 23.003 [23] with the last 4 digits of the SNR masked by setting the corresponding bits to 1. The first to fourth bits correspond to the first digit of the IMEISV, the fifth to eighth bits correspond to the second digit of the IMEISV, and so on.

section_list.name: New Security Context Indicator
aoa: 9.3.1.55 New Security Context Indicator IE Semantics: This IE indicates that the AMF has activated a new 5G NAS security context as described in TS 33.501 [13]. The NSCI as defined in TS 33.501 [13].

aoa: 9.3.1.56 Time to Wait IE Semantics: This IE defines the minimum allowed waiting time.

section_list.name: UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate
aoa: 9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per UE which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and a subscription parameter provided by the AMF to the NG-RAN node. Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows.

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.58 UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: This IE indicates the UE Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

section_list.name: Security Result
aoa: This IE indicates whether the security policy indicated as "preferred" in the Security Indication IE is performed or not.
9.3.1.59 Integrity Protection Result IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP integrity protection is performed or not for the concerned PDU session.
9.3.1.59 Confidentiality Protection Result IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP ciphering is performed or not for the concerned PDU session.

section_list.name: User Plane Security Information
aoa: This IE indicates user plane security information related to security policy.
9.3.1.59 Security Result - Section Description: This IE indicates whether the security policy indicated as "preferred" in the Security Indication IE is performed or not.
9.3.1.59 Integrity Protection Result IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP integrity protection is performed or not for the concerned PDU session.
9.3.1.59 Confidentiality Protection Result IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP ciphering is performed or not for the concerned PDU session.

9.3.1.27 Security Indication - Section Description: This IE contains the user plane integrity protection indication and confidentiality protection indication which indicates the requirements on UP integrity protection and ciphering for corresponding PDU sessions, respectively. Additionally, this IE contains the maximum integrity protected data rate per UE for integrity protection for DRBs.
9.3.1.27 Integrity Protection Indication IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP integrity protection shall apply, should apply or shall not apply for the concerned PDU session.
9.3.1.27 Confidentiality Protection Indication IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP ciphering shall apply, should apply or shall not apply for the concerned PDU session.

9.3.1.27 - Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate Uplink IE - ifIntegrityProtectionRequiredorPreferred: This IE shall be present if the Integrity Protection Indication IE within the Security Indication IE is set to “required” or “preferred”. 9.3.1.27 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate Uplink IE Semantics: Indicates the maximum aggregate rate for integrity protected DRBs supported by the UE in UL. If the Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate Downlink IE is absent, this IE applies to both UL and DL. 9.3.1.103 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the maximum aggregate data rate for integrity protected DRBs for a UE as defined in TS 38.300 [8]. 9.3.1.103 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate IE Semantics: Defines the upper bound of the aggregate data rate of user plane integrity protected data for either UL or DL.

9.3.1.27 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate Downlink IE Semantics: Indicates the maximum aggregate rate for integrity protected DRBs supported by the UE in the DL. 9.3.1.103 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the maximum aggregate data rate for integrity protected DRBs for a UE as defined in TS 38.300 [8]. 9.3.1.103 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate IE Semantics: Defines the upper bound of the aggregate data rate of user plane integrity protected data for either UL or DL.

section_list.name: Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority
aoa: 9.3.1.61 Index to RAT/Frequency Selection Priority IE Semantics: This IE is used to define local configuration for RRM strategies such as camp priorities in Idle mode and control of inter-RAT/inter-frequency handover in Active mode (see TS 23.501 [9]).

section_list.name: Data Forwarding Accepted
aoa: 9.3.1.62 Data Forwarding Accepted IE Semantics: This IE indicates that the NG-RAN node accepts the proposed DL data forwarding for the QoS flow which is subject to data forwarding.

section_list.name: Data Forwarding Not Possible
aoa: 9.3.1.63 Data Forwarding Not Possible IE Semantics: This IE indicates that the 5GC decided that the corresponding PDU session will not be subject to data forwarding.

section_list.name: Direct Forwarding Path Availability
aoa: 9.3.1.64 Direct Forwarding Path Availability IE Semantics: This IE indicates whether a direct forwarding path is available.

9.3.1.71 Recommended Cell Item IE Semantics: Includes visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.

9.3.2.2 UP Transport Layer Information - Section Description: This IE is used to provide the NG user plane transport layer information associated with a PDU session for an NG-RAN node - AMF pair. In this release it corresponds to an IP address and a GTP Tunnel Endpoint Identifier.

9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].

9.3.2.5 GTP-TEID - Section Description: This IE is the GTP Tunnel Endpoint Identifier to be used for the user plane transport between the NG-RAN node and the UPF. 9.3.2.5 GTP-TEID IE Semantics: For details and range, see TS 29.281 [15].

section_list.name: Paging Priority
aoa: ENUMERATED (PrioLevel1, PrioLevel2, PrioLevel3, PrioLevel4, PrioLevel5, PrioLevel6, PrioLevel7, PrioLevel8, …)
9.3.1.78 Paging Priority IE Semantics: This element indicates the paging priority for paging a UE. Lower value codepoint indicates higher priority.

section_list.name: Packet Loss Rate
aoa: 9.3.1.79 Packet Loss Rate IE Semantics: This IE indicates the Packet Loss Rate for a QoS flow. Ratio of lost packets per number of packets sent, expressed in tenth of percent.

section_list.name: Packet Delay Budget
aoa: 9.3.1.80 Packet Delay Budget IE Semantics: This IE indicates the Packet Delay Budget for a QoS flow. Upper bound value for the delay that a packet may experience expressed in unit of 0.5ms.

section_list.name: Packet Error Rate
aoa: This IE indicates the Packet Error Rate for a QoS flow.
9.3.1.81 Scalar IE Semantics: The packet error rate is expressed as Scalar x 10-k where k is the Exponent.

section_list.name: Averaging Window
aoa: 9.3.1.82 Averaging Window IE Semantics: This IE indicates the Averaging Window for a QoS flow, and applies to GBR QoS flows only. Unit: ms. The default value of the IE is 2000ms.

section_list.name: Maximum Data Burst Volume
aoa: 9.3.1.83 Maximum Data Burst Volume IE Semantics: This IE indicates the Maximum Data Burst Volume for a QoS flow, and applies to delay critical GBR QoS flows only. Unit: byte.

section_list.name: Priority Level
aoa: 9.3.1.84 Priority Level IE Semantics: This IE indicates the Priority Level for a QoS flow. Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 127 as the lowest priority.

section_list.name: Mobility Restriction List
aoa: This IE defines roaming or access restrictions for subsequent mobility action for which the NG-RAN provides information about the target of the mobility action towards the UE, e.g., handover, or for SCG selection during dual connectivity operation or for assigning proper RNAs. NG-RAN behaviour upon receiving this IE is specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).

9.3.1.85 Equivalent PLMNs IE Semantics: Allowed PLMNs in addition to Serving PLMN. This list corresponds to the list of "equivalent PLMNs" as defined in TS 24.501 [26]. section_list.name: UE Security Capabilities
aoa: This IE defines the supported algorithms for encryption and integrity protection in the UE.

9.3.1.86 NR Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NEA0, "first bit" – 128-NEA1, "second bit" – 128-NEA2, "third bit" – 128-NEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 NR Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an integrity protection algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than NIA0, "first bit" – 128-NIA1, "second bit" – 128-NIA2, "third bit" – 128-NIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Encryption Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EEA0, "first bit" – 128-EEA1, "second bit" – 128-EEA2, "third bit" – 128-EEA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

9.3.1.86 E-UTRA Integrity Protection Algorithms IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents an encryption algorithm: "all bits equal to 0" – UE supports no other algorithm than EIA0, "first bit" – 128-EIA1, "second bit" – 128-EIA2, "third bit" – 128-EIA3, other bits reserved for future use. Value '1' indicates support and value '0' indicates no support of the algorithm. Algorithms are defined in TS 33.401 [27].

section_list.name: Security Key
aoa: 9.3.1.87 Security Key IE Semantics: This IE is used to apply security in the NG-RAN for different scenarios as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. Key material for NG-RAN node or Next Hop Key as defined in TS 33.501 [13]

section_list.name: Security Context
aoa: This IE provides security related parameters to the NG-RAN node which are used to derive security keys for user plane traffic and RRC signalling messages and for security parameter generation for subsequent mobility, see TS 33.501 [13].
9.3.1.88 Next Hop Chaining Count IE Semantics: Next Hop Chaining Counter (NCC) defined in TS 33.501 [13].

9.3.1.88 Next-Hop NH IE Semantics: The NH together with the NCC is used to derive the security configuration as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key - Section Description: This IE is used to apply security in the NG-RAN for different scenarios as defined in TS 33.501 [13]. 9.3.1.87 Security Key IE Semantics: Key material for NG-RAN node or Next Hop Key as defined in TS 33.501 [13]

section_list.name: Paging DRX

9.3.1.91 RRC Inactive Transition Report Request IE Semantics: This IE is used to request the NG-RAN node to report or stop reporting to the 5GC when the UE enters or leaves RRC_INACTIVE state.

section_list.name: RRC State
aoa: 9.3.1.92 RRC State IE Semantics: This IE indicates the RRC state of the UE. Indicates the current RRC state of the UE.

section_list.name: Expected UE Behaviour
aoa: This IE indicates the behaviour of a UE with predictable activity and/or mobility behaviour, to assist the NG-RAN node in e.g. determining the optimum RRC connection time or helping with the RRC_INACTIVE state transition and RNA configuration (e.g. size and shape of the RNA).
9.3.1.94 Expected UE Activity Behaviour - Section Description: This IE indicates information about the expected "UE activity behaviour" as defined in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.94 Expected Activity Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected activity time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected activity time in [seconds].
9.3.1.94 Expected Idle Period IE Semantics: If set to "181" the expected idle time is longer than 180 seconds. The remaining values indicate the expected idle time in [seconds].

9.3.1.94 Source of UE Activity Behaviour Information IE Semantics: If "subscription information" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from subscription information. If "statistics" is indicated, the information contained in the Expected Activity Period IE and the Expected Idle Period IE, if present, is derived from statistical information.
ENUMERATED (sec15, sec30, sec60, sec90, sec120, sec180, long-time, …)

9.3.1.93 Expected HO Interval IE Semantics: Indicates the expected time interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers. If "long-time" is included, the interval between inter NG-RAN node handovers is expected to be longer than 180 seconds.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Mobility IE Semantics: Indicates whether the UE is expected to be stationary or mobile.
9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory IE Semantics: Indicates the UE's expected geographical movement.

9.3.1.93 Expected UE Moving Trajectory Item IE Semantics: Includes list of visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.

9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

This IE provides information on recommended cells and NG-RAN nodes for paging.
9.3.1.71 Recommended Cells for Paging - Section Description: This IE contains the recommended cells for paging. This IE is transparent to the 5GC.

9.3.1.71 Recommended Cell Item IE Semantics: Includes visited and non-visited cells, where visited cells are listed in the order the UE visited them with the most recent cell being the first in the list. Non-visited cells are included immediately after the visited cell they are associated with.
9.3.1.73 NG-RAN CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify a cell in NG-RAN.
9.3.1.7 NR CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an NR cell (see TS 38.300 [8]).

9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity - Section Description: This IE indicates the PLMN Identity. 9.3.3.5 PLMN Identity IE Semantics: Digits 0 to 9 encoded 0000 to 1001, 1111 used as filler digit. Two digits per octet: - bits 4 to 1 of octet n encoding digit 2n-1 - bits 8 to 5 of octet n encoding digit 2n PLMN Identity consists of 3 digits from MCC followed by either: - a filler digit plus 2 digits from MNC (in case of 2 digit MNC) or - 3 digits from MNC (in case of 3 digit MNC).
9.3.1.7 NR Cell Identity IE Semantics: The leftmost bits of the NR Cell Identity IE correspond to the gNB ID (defined in subclause 9.3.1.6).
9.3.1.9 E-UTRA CGI - Section Description: This IE is used to globally identify an E-UTRA cell (see TS 36.300 [17]).

9.3.1.102 PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per PDU session which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and is provided by the SMF to the NG-RAN node. Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows.
├─PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink

9.3.1.102 PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: Indicates the PDU session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s
└─PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink

9.3.1.102 PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: Indicates the PDU session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.1.108 UL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN of the first missing UL PDCP SDU in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.108 Receive Status of UL PDCP SDUs IE Semantics: The IE is used in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. The first bit indicates the status of the SDU after the First Missing UL PDCP SDU. The Nth bit indicates the status of the UL PDCP SDU in position (N + First Missing SDU Number) modulo (1 + the maximum value of the PDCP-SN). 0: PDCP SDU has not been received. 1: PDCP SDU has been received correctly.

9.3.1.108 UL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN of the first missing UL PDCP SDU in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN.

The Nth bit indicates the status of the UL PDCP SDU in position (N + First Missing SDU Number) modulo (1 + the maximum value of the PDCP-SN). 0: PDCP SDU has not been received. 1: PDCP SDU has been received correctly.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.109 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 12 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 12 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.108 DL COUNT Value IE Semantics: PDCP-SN and HFN that the target NG-RAN node should assign for the next DL PDCP SDU not having an SN yet in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN. 9.3.1.110 COUNT Value for PDCP SN Length 18 - Section Description: This IE contains a PDCP sequence number and a hyper frame number in case of 18 bit long PDCP-SN.

9.3.1.126 Primary RAT Restriction IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a RAT. If a bit is set to "1", the respective RAT is restricted for the UE. If a bit is set to "0", the respective RAT is not restricted for the UE. Bits 3-7 reserved for future use. The Primary RAT is the RAT used in the access cell, or target cell.
BIT STRING { e-UTRA (0), nR (1), e-UTRA-unlicensed (2), nR-unlicensed (3)} (SIZE (8, …))

9.3.1.126 Secondary RAT Restriction IE Semantics: Each position in the bitmap represents a RAT. If a bit is set to "1", the respective RAT is restricted for the UE. If a bit is set to "0", the respective RAT is not restricted for the UE. Bits 4-7 reserved for future use. A Secondary RAT is a RAT used in any cell serving the UE excluding the PCell.

section_list.name: Periodic Registration Update Timer
aoa: 9.3.3.24 Periodic Registration Update Timer IE Semantics: This IE is used to assist NG-RAN to generate corresponding timer for periodic RNA update for RRC_INACTIVE UEs. Bits 5 to 1 represent the binary coded timer value. Bits 6 to 8 define the timer value unit for the Periodic Registration Update Timer as follows: Bits 8 7 6 0 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 minutes 0 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour 0 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 10 hours 0 1 1 value is incremented in multiples of 2 seconds 1 0 0 value is incremented in multiples of 30 seconds 1 0 1 value is incremented in multiples of 1 minute 1 1 1 value indicates that the timer is deactivated. 1 1 0 value is incremented in multiples of 1 hour in this version of the protocol.

aoa: PDU Session Resource Setup Request Transfer
This IE is transparent to the AMF.

9.3.4.1 PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: This IE shall be present when at least one Non-GBR QoS flow is being setup and is ignored otherwise. 9.3.1.102 PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE is applicable for all Non-GBR QoS flows per PDU session which is defined for the downlink and the uplink direction and is provided by the SMF to the NG-RAN node. 9.3.1.102 PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate IE Semantics: Applicable for Non-GBR QoS flows.
│  ├─PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink

9.3.1.102 PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Downlink IE Semantics: Indicates the PDU session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the downlink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s
│  └─PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink

9.3.1.102 PDU Session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate Uplink IE Semantics: Indicates the PDU session Aggregate Maximum Bit Rate as specified in TS 23.501 [9] in the uplink direction. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the number of bits delivered by NG-RAN in UL or to NG-RAN in DL within a period of time, divided by the duration of the period. It is used, for example, to indicate the maximum or guaranteed bit rate for a GBR QoS flow, or an aggregate maximum bit rate. 9.3.1.4 Bit Rate IE Semantics: The unit is: bit/s

9.3.4.1 UL NG-U UP TNL Information IE Semantics: UPF endpoint of the NG-U transport bearer, for delivery of UL PDUs. 9.3.2.2 UP Transport Layer Information - Section Description: This IE is used to provide the NG user plane transport layer information associated with a PDU session for an NG-RAN node - AMF pair. In this release it corresponds to an IP address and a GTP Tunnel Endpoint Identifier.

9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].

9.3.2.5 GTP-TEID - Section Description: This IE is the GTP Tunnel Endpoint Identifier to be used for the user plane transport between the NG-RAN node and the UPF. 9.3.2.5 GTP-TEID IE Semantics: For details and range, see TS 29.281 [15].

9.3.4.1 Additional UL NG-U UP TNL Information IE Semantics: UPF endpoint of the additional NG-U transport bearer(s), for delivery of UL PDUs for split PDU session. 9.3.2.12 UP Transport Layer Information List - Section Description: This IE is used to provide a list of additional UP transport layer information for a split PDU session.

9.3.2.2 UP Transport Layer Information - Section Description: This IE is used to provide the NG user plane transport layer information associated with a PDU session for an NG-RAN node - AMF pair. In this release it corresponds to an IP address and a GTP Tunnel Endpoint Identifier.

9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address - Section Description: This IE is an IP address. 9.3.2.4 Transport Layer Address IE Semantics: The Radio Network Layer is not supposed to interpret the address information. It should pass it to the Transport Layer for interpretation. For details, see TS 38.414 [14].

9.3.2.5 GTP-TEID - Section Description: This IE is the GTP Tunnel Endpoint Identifier to be used for the user plane transport between the NG-RAN node and the UPF. 9.3.2.5 GTP-TEID IE Semantics: For details and range, see TS 29.281 [15].

9.3.4.1 Data Forwarding Not Possible IE Semantics: This IE may be present in case of HANDOVER REQUEST message and is ignored otherwise. 9.3.1.63 Data Forwarding Not Possible - Section Description: This IE indicates that the 5GC decided that the corresponding PDU session will not be subject to data forwarding.
9.3.1.52 PDU Session Type - Section Description: This IE indicates the PDU Session Type as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.27 Security Indication - Section Description: This IE contains the user plane integrity protection indication and confidentiality protection indication which indicates the requirements on UP integrity protection and ciphering for corresponding PDU sessions, respectively. Additionally, this IE contains the maximum integrity protected data rate per UE for integrity protection for DRBs.
9.3.1.27 Integrity Protection Indication IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP integrity protection shall apply, should apply or shall not apply for the concerned PDU session.
9.3.1.27 Confidentiality Protection Indication IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP ciphering shall apply, should apply or shall not apply for the concerned PDU session.

9.3.1.27 - Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate Uplink IE - ifIntegrityProtectionRequiredorPreferred: This IE shall be present if the Integrity Protection Indication IE within the Security Indication IE is set to “required” or “preferred”. 9.3.1.27 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate Uplink IE Semantics: Indicates the maximum aggregate rate for integrity protected DRBs supported by the UE in UL. If the Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate Downlink IE is absent, this IE applies to both UL and DL. 9.3.1.103 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the maximum aggregate data rate for integrity protected DRBs for a UE as defined in TS 38.300 [8]. 9.3.1.103 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate IE Semantics: Defines the upper bound of the aggregate data rate of user plane integrity protected data for either UL or DL.

9.3.1.27 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate Downlink IE Semantics: Indicates the maximum aggregate rate for integrity protected DRBs supported by the UE in the DL. 9.3.1.103 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate - Section Description: This IE indicates the maximum aggregate data rate for integrity protected DRBs for a UE as defined in TS 38.300 [8]. 9.3.1.103 Maximum Integrity Protected Data Rate IE Semantics: Defines the upper bound of the aggregate data rate of user plane integrity protected data for either UL or DL.

9.3.4.1 Network Instance IE Semantics: This IE is ignored if the Common Network Instance IE is included. 9.3.1.113 Network Instance - Section Description: This IE provides the network instance to be used by the NG-RAN node when selecting a particular transport network resource as described in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.51 QoS Flow Identifier - Section Description: This IE identifies a QoS flow within a PDU Session. The definition and use of the QoS Flow Identifier is specified in TS 23.501 [9].
9.3.1.12 QoS Flow Level QoS Parameters - Section Description: This IE defines the QoS parameters to be applied to a QoS flow.
9.3.1.28 Non Dynamic 5QI Descriptor - Section Description: This IE indicates the QoS Characteristics for a standardized or pre-configured 5QI for downlink and uplink.
9.3.1.28 5QI IE Semantics: Indicates the standardized or pre-configured 5QI as specified in TS 23.501 [9].

9.3.1.28 Priority Level IE Semantics: Priority Level is specified in TS 23.501 [9]. When included, it overrides standardized or pre-configured value. 9.3.1.84 Priority Level - Section Description: This IE indicates the Priority Level for a QoS flow. 9.3.1.84 Priority Level IE Semantics: Values ordered in decreasing order of priority, i.e. with 1 as the highest priority and 127 as the lowest priority.

9.3.1.27 Security Indication - Section Description: This IE contains the user plane integrity protection indication and confidentiality protection indication which indicates the requirements on UP integrity protection and ciphering for corresponding PDU sessions, respectively. Additionally, this IE contains the maximum integrity protected data rate per UE for integrity protection for DRBs.
9.3.1.27 Integrity Protection Indication IE Semantics: Indicates whether UP integrity protection shall apply, should apply or shall not apply for the concerned PDU session.
